    "memory_id": "ghm_001",
    "title": "NYC DOB Filing Checklist — Complete step-by-step for NYC building permits",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`NYC Department of Buildings (DOB) Permit Filing — Complete Step-by-Step Guide\n\nOVERVIEW\nFiling for a New York City building permit requires navigating the DOB NOW: Build portal, assembling a compliant set of drawings, and coordinating with multiple city agencies. This guide covers the full process from project scoping through permit issuance for new buildings, alterations, and demolitions.\n\nSTEP 1 — DETERMINE APPLICATION TYPE\nNYC DOB uses four primary application types:\n- NB (New Building): Full demolition of existing structure followed by new construction, or construction on a vacant lot.\n- ALT1 (Alteration Type 1): Change of use, occupancy, or egress. Requires full new certificate of occupancy.\n- ALT2 (Alteration Type 2): Multiple types of work that do not change use or egress. Requires plan examination.\n- ALT3 (Alteration Type 3): Single type of minor work. No plan examination required; work permit issued directly.\n- DM (Demolition): Full or partial demolition. Requires separate demolition permit before NB filing.\n\nFor projects in landmarks districts, add LPC (Landmarks Preservation Commission) pre-approval before DOB submission.\n\nSTEP 2 — ENGAGE A LICENSED DESIGN PROFESSIONAL\nAll ALT1, ALT2, and NB applications must be filed by a NYS-licensed Professional Engineer (PE) or Registered Architect (RA) holding a current NYC DOB registration. Verify registration status at the DOB's eFiling portal. The design professional becomes the \"Applicant of Record\" and bears legal responsibility for code compliance.\n\nSTEP 3 — ZONING COMPLIANCE VERIFICATION\nBefore drawing one line, confirm zoning:\n- Look up the zoning lot using the NYC Zoning Resolution and ZoLa (Zoning & Land use Application) map at zola.planning.nyc.gov.\n- Determine FAR (Floor Area Ratio), setbacks, height limits, and required open space ratios.\n- Identify applicable Special Purpose Districts (e.g., Special Midtown District, Special Hudson Yards District).\n- If a zoning variance or special permit is needed, file with the Board of Standards and Appeals (BSA) or City Planning Commission (CPC) first. DOB will not accept a permit application that conflicts with zoning.\n\nSTEP 4 — SPECIAL APPROVALS AND AGENCY SIGNOFFS\nDepending on project scope, secure pre-approvals from:\n- FDNY: Required for fire suppression systems, standpipes, smoke control, and high-rise occupancies. File via DOB NOW and FDNY's permitting system simultaneously.\n- DEP (Dept. of Environmental Protection): Sewer connection, water tap, backflow prevention, and asbestos/PCB abatement registrations.\n- DOT (Dept. of Transportation): Sidewalk, curb cut, or street-opening permits. Scaffold over the roadway requires separate DOT permit.\n- HPD (Dept. of Housing Preservation and Development): For affordable housing projects or alterations in HPD-regulated buildings.\n- SBS/EDC: If the project involves industrial business zones or economic development incentives.\n- ConEd/National Grid: For new or upgraded utility service entrance — utility company sign-off required on electrical and gas permits.\n\nSTEP 5 — PREPARE DRAWING SET\nAll drawings must be on 30\"×42\" or 24\"×36\" sheets (ANSI D or E size). Required sheets:\n1. Title Sheet: Project address, block/lot, BIN (Building Identification Number), owner info, design professional seal, applicable codes, and occupancy classification.\n2. Site Plan: Lot dimensions, building footprint, setbacks, adjacent structures, zoning calculations (FAR, lot coverage, open space).\n3. Architectural Plans: Floor plans at 1/8\" = 1'-0\" minimum scale for all floors including cellar, roof, and mechanical levels. Show all rooms, corridors, stairs, shafts, and means of egress.\n4. Sections and Elevations: Minimum two cross-sections through the building; all exterior elevations.\n5. Details: Construction assembly details per NYC BC Chapter 7 (fire-resistance) and Chapter 10 (means of egress).\n6. Structural Drawings: Foundation plan, framing plans, connection details, and load calculations. Engineer's stamp required.\n7. MEP (Mechanical/Electrical/Plumbing): Separate stamped drawings for each discipline.\n8. Energy Code Compliance: COMcheck or REScheck printout, or ASHRAE 90.1 compliance documentation. NYC Local Law 97 carbon compliance narrative for buildings over 25,000 SF.\n9. Accessibility: ADA/NYC BC Chapter 11 compliance plan showing accessible routes, ramps, restroom layouts.\n\nSTEP 6 — DOB NOW: BUILD SUBMISSION\nLog into DOB NOW: Build at dobonline.nyc.gov:\n1. Create a new job filing. Assign filing type (NB, ALT1, ALT2, ALT3, DM).\n2. Enter property information (BBL — Borough, Block, Lot — and BIN).\n3. Select applicable work types (e.g., GC-General Construction, PL-Plumbing, ME-Mechanical, EL-Electrical, FA-Fire Alarm, SP-Sprinkler).\n4. Upload drawings as individual PDFs (max 50 MB each). Use DOB's file naming convention: [BIN]_[WorkType]_[SheetNumber].\n5. Complete the PW1 (Plan Work) form: construction cost estimate, square footage, proposed use.\n6. Attach owner authorization (notarized letter) if the applicant is not the property owner.\n7. Pay filing fees at time of submission. Fee schedule: NB/ALT1 = $0.26/SF with minimums; ALT2/ALT3 = flat or per-work-type fees. Check current DOB fee schedule as fees update annually.\n\nSTEP 7 — PLAN EXAMINATION\nDOB assigns a Plan Examiner. Two pathways:\n- Standard Review: Examiner reviews within 10–20 business days (target). Objections returned via DOB NOW portal.\n- Professional Certification (Pro-Cert): Licensed PE/RA self-certifies code compliance. Permit issued within 24–48 hours. Subject to mandatory audit (10–15% of filings randomly selected for full DOB review post-permit).\n\nRespond to all objections within the same DOB NOW job. Upload revised drawings using the \"Revision\" function; do not create a new job.\n\nSTEP 8 — SPECIAL INSPECTIONS AND CONTROLLED INSPECTIONS\nPer NYC BC Chapter 17, many work types require Special Inspections by an approved Special Inspection Agency (SIA):\n- High-strength bolting, welding, steel frame erection\n- Concrete mix design and placement\n- Masonry construction\n- Soils and foundations\n- Sprayed fire-resistive materials (SFRM)\nFile the TR1 (Technical Report Statement of Responsibility) form in DOB NOW before the first inspection.\n\nSTEP 9 — PERMIT ISSUANCE AND POSTING\nOnce approved, download and print the approved permit card (NYC DOB permit placard) from DOB NOW. Post at the job site in a weatherproof holder visible from the street. The approved drawings must be kept on-site at all times for inspector review.\n\nSTEP 10 — INSPECTIONS DURING CONSTRUCTION\nSchedule required Progress Inspections via DOB NOW:\n- Foundations (before pouring)\n- Framing (rough-in)\n- Fireproofing\n- Electrical rough-in (by NYC DOB Electrical Inspector)\n- Plumbing rough-in and pressure test (by NYC DEP Inspector)\n- Final (all work complete, before Certificate of Occupancy application)\n\nSTEP 11 — CERTIFICATE OF OCCUPANCY\nAfter final inspection approval:\n1. Resolve all open violations and objections.\n2. File CO application via DOB NOW.\n3. Submit all required sign-offs from FDNY, DOT, DEP, and other agencies.\n4. Pay CO fee.\n5. DOB issues a Temporary Certificate of Occupancy (TCO) if minor items remain, valid for 90 days. Full CO issued when all items are cleared.\n\nKEY CONTACTS AND RESOURCES\n- DOB NOW Portal: dobonline.nyc.gov\n- DOB Help Center: nyc.gov/site/buildings\n- NYC Building Code (2022): Based on IBC 2018 with local amendments\n- Zoning Resolution: zr.planning.nyc.gov\n- DOB NOW training videos: Available on DOB website under \"Training\"",
