    "title": "California CBC 2022 Seismic Requirements — Zone-by-zone requirements",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`California Building Code 2022 — Seismic Design Requirements by Zone\n\nOVERVIEW\nCalifornia uses the 2022 California Building Code (CBC), which is based on the International Building Code (IBC) 2021 with California amendments. Seismic design in California is governed by CBC Chapter 16 and ASCE 7-22. California does not use traditional \"seismic zones\" per se — instead, it uses Site Classes and Seismic Design Categories (SDC) derived from mapped spectral accelerations from the USGS Unified Hazard Tool.\n\nSEISMIC DESIGN CATEGORIES (SDC)\nBuildings are assigned SDC A through F based on occupancy (Risk Category I–IV) and mapped ground motion parameters (SS and S1 at the building site).\n\nSDC A: Very low seismic hazard. Minimal seismic detailing required. Essentially no seismic design force beyond basic structural integrity.\n\nSDC B: Low seismic hazard. Basic seismic detailing per ASCE 7-22 Section 12.14 (simplified procedure permitted for simple structures). Lateral system must be present but detailing requirements are modest.\n\nSDC C: Moderate seismic hazard. Intermediate moment frames (IMF), intermediate shear walls, or equivalent systems required. Irregularity restrictions begin to apply. Redundancy factor ρ applies.\n\nSDC D: High seismic hazard — applies to most of coastal California including Los Angeles Basin, Bay Area, and San Diego. This is the most common SDC for California buildings.\n- Special Moment-Resisting Frames (SMRF) per AISC 341 or ACI 318 Chapter 18 required for frame systems.\n- Special Reinforced Concrete Shear Walls or Special Structural Steel Walls required for wall systems.\n- Redundancy factor ρ = 1.3 unless redundancy criteria in ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.4.2 are met.\n- Collector elements designed for amplified seismic loads (Ω₀ = 3.0 for most systems).\n- Diaphragm design per ASCE 7-22 Section 12.10.\n- Drift limits: δmax ≤ 0.020 hsx for Risk Category I and II; 0.015 hsx for Risk Category III; 0.010 hsx for Risk Category IV.\n- P-delta effects must be checked per ASCE 7-22 Section 12.8.7.\n\nSDC E and F: Very high seismic hazard (near active fault zones). SDC E applies to Risk Category I/II buildings with S1 ≥ 0.75g. SDC F applies to Risk Category III/IV buildings with S1 ≥ 0.75g.\n- All SDC D requirements apply.\n- Certain structural systems are prohibited (e.g., ordinary moment frames, ordinary shear walls).\n- Base isolation and supplemental energy dissipation systems are encouraged and may be required by CBC amendments for certain essential facilities.\n- Nonstructural components must meet enhanced anchorage requirements per ASCE 7-22 Chapter 13.\n\nSITE CLASSES\nSite Class is determined by the average shear wave velocity (Vs30) in the top 30 meters of soil:\n- Site Class A: Hard rock, Vs30 > 5000 ft/s (1500 m/s)\n- Site Class B: Rock, Vs30 = 2500–5000 ft/s (760–1500 m/s)\n- Site Class C: Very dense soil/soft rock, Vs30 = 1200–2500 ft/s (360–760 m/s)\n- Site Class D (Default): Stiff soil, Vs30 = 600–1200 ft/s (180–360 m/s) — used when site-specific data unavailable\n- Site Class E: Soft clay, Vs30 < 600 ft/s (< 180 m/s) — requires site-specific hazard analysis in SDC D/E/F\n- Site Class F: Liquefiable soils, quick and highly sensitive clays, collapsible weakly cemented soils, peats, or very high plasticity clays — always requires site-specific geotechnical investigation\n\nREGIONAL REQUIREMENTS BY MAJOR CALIFORNIA AREA\n\nLOS ANGELES COUNTY (Most Areas)\n- SS (0.2s spectral acceleration): Typically 1.5g–2.0g+\n- S1 (1.0s spectral acceleration): Typically 0.6g–0.9g+\n- SDC: D to F depending on proximity to Puente Hills, Sierra Madre, Newport-Inglewood faults\n- Near-fault factors Na and Nv apply for sites within 10 km of known active faults (Class A or B per CBC)\n- Seismic hazard disclosure required in real estate transactions per California law\n- Los Angeles City amendments: Mandatory Retrofit Program for non-ductile concrete buildings (LAMC 91.9334); soft-story wood frame retrofits required per LAMC 91.9323\n\nSAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA\n- SS: Typically 1.5g–2.5g+ (highest near Hayward and San Andreas faults)\n- S1: Typically 0.6g–1.0g+\n- SDC: D to F\n- Bay mud and Delta deposits (Site Class E/F) common — liquefaction risk zones mapped by CGS\n- City of San Francisco amendments: Mandatory Soft-Story Retrofit (SFBC 4D)\n- East Bay: Orinda/Moraga/Lafayette have moderate to high hazard; proximity to Calaveras and Hayward faults critical\n- Tall wood buildings (CLT/mass timber) above 85 ft require CBC Chapter 19 (Alternative Means and Methods) approval\n\nSAN DIEGO COUNTY\n- SS: Typically 1.0g–1.5g\n- S1: Typically 0.4g–0.6g\n- SDC: C to D\n- Rose Canyon Fault runs through downtown San Diego — proximity triggers near-fault amplification\n- Coastal sites: Liquefiable beach deposits (Site Class E/F) in Mission Bay, Coronado areas\n\nINLAND EMPIRE (San Bernardino/Riverside)\n- SS: Typically 1.5g–2.0g (proximity to San Jacinto and San Andreas faults)\n- S1: Typically 0.6g–0.8g\n- SDC: D to F\n- San Bernardino Valley has extensive alluvial deposits — Site Class D common, E in some areas\n- Whittier Narrows: High amplification zone\n\nCENTRAL VALLEY (Sacramento, Fresno, Bakersfield)\n- SS: Typically 0.5g–1.0g (lower in Sacramento, higher toward Fresno)\n- S1: Typically 0.2g–0.4g\n- SDC: B to D\n- Less stringent detailing generally required than coastal California\n- Bakersfield: Proximity to White Wolf and Garlock faults elevates hazard\n\nNORTHERN CALIFORNIA (Eureka, Redding, Chico)\n- SS: Varies widely — Eureka area 1.5g+ (Cascadia subduction zone risk); interior valleys 0.5g–1.0g\n- SDC: C to D\n- Cascadia Subduction Zone: Long-return-period very large earthquake (M8.0–9.0) modifies risk for essential facilities in coastal Northern California\n\nSEISMIC DESIGN PROCEDURE SELECTION (CBC 2022 / ASCE 7-22)\nEquivalent Lateral Force (ELF) Procedure (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.8): Permitted for SDC B–D if building meets all regularity criteria and height limits (typically ≤ 160 ft for SDC D).\nModal Response Spectrum Analysis (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.9): Required for irregular structures in SDC D–F.\nSeismic Response History Procedures (ASCE 7-22 Section 16): Required for SDC D–F buildings with base isolation or energy dissipation systems; optional for irregular structures.\nSite-Specific Hazard Analysis (ASCE 7-22 Section 21): Required for Site Class F; required for SDC E/F in certain configurations; may reduce design forces if spectrum is lower than generic mapped values.\n\nCALIFORNIA-SPECIFIC AMENDMENTS TO ASCE 7-22\n- CBC Section 1613.1: California adopts ASCE 7-22 for seismic with the following modifications:\n- Risk-Targeted Maximum Considered Earthquake (MCER) maps are replaced with California-specific maps developed by USGS in partnership with California Geological Survey (CGS) for certain applications.\n- Essential facilities (Risk Category IV) in SDC E/F must use site-specific ground motion procedures.\n- CBC Section 1705 (Special Inspections): Expanded list of special inspection requirements for seismic force-resisting systems compared to IBC baseline.\n\nKEY REFERENCE DOCUMENTS\n- CBC 2022 (Title 24, Part 2)\n- ASCE 7-22 (Minimum Design Loads and Associated Criteria for Buildings)\n- AISC 341-22 (Seismic Provisions for Structural Steel Buildings)\n- ACI 318-19 (Building Code Requirements for Structural Concrete)\n- USGS Unified Hazard Tool: earthquake.usgs.gov/hazards/designmaps\n- California Geological Survey Seismic Hazard Zones: maps.conservation.ca.gov/cgs/shmp",
    "price_usdc": 0,
