    "memory_id": "ghm_006",
    "title": "Wood Frame Shear Wall Design Guide — Per IBC 2021",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`Wood Frame Shear Wall Design Guide — IBC 2021 and SDPWS 2021\n\nOVERVIEW\nWood-frame shear walls resist lateral forces (wind and seismic) in wood-frame buildings. This guide covers the design of wood structural panel (WSP) shear walls per IBC 2021, which references AWC SDPWS-2021 (Special Design Provisions for Wind and Seismic) as its primary standard for wood shear wall design.\n\nSHEAR WALL TYPES\n\nType I — Traditional Shear Walls (SDPWS Section 4.3)\nSheathed with wood structural panels (plywood or OSB) on one or both sides. Full-height sheathing panels required. Openings are not permitted within the shear wall segment unless designed per SDPWS Section 4.3.5 (force transfer around openings method).\n\nType II — Perforated Shear Walls (SDPWS Section 4.3.5.3)\nAllows openings within the shear wall. Full-height sheathing panels flank the openings. Design uses Perforated Shear Wall (PSW) method with reduction factor Cop based on opening area ratio. Less hardware required; less capacity than Type I for equivalent length.\n\nType III — Force Transfer Around Openings (FTAO) (SDPWS Section 4.3.5.2)\nFull capacity maintained above and below openings using blocking, straps, and hold-downs around each opening. Higher capacity than perforated method; more hardware and complexity.\n\nNOMINAL UNIT SHEAR CAPACITIES — WSP SHEAR WALLS\nPer SDPWS 2021 Table 4.3A (for seismic) and Table 4.3B (for wind):\nValues are Nominal Unit Shear (lbs/ft) — apply reduction factors for ASD or LRFD.\n\nOSB or Plywood, Blocked, Douglas Fir-Larch Framing:\n\nPanel Thickness | Edge Nail Spacing | Nominal Capacity (Seismic) | Nominal Capacity (Wind)\n3/8\"           | 6\"                | 640 plf                    | 730 plf\n3/8\"           | 4\"                | 870 plf                    | 1,020 plf\n3/8\"           | 3\"                | 1,190 plf                  | 1,370 plf\n7/16\"          | 6\"                | 730 plf                    | 840 plf\n7/16\"          | 4\"                | 980 plf                    | 1,120 plf\n7/16\"          | 3\"                | 1,330 plf                  | 1,530 plf\n15/32\" or 1/2\" | 6\"                | 870 plf                    | 1,000 plf\n15/32\" or 1/2\" | 4\"                | 1,190 plf                  | 1,370 plf\n15/32\" or 1/2\" | 3\"                | 1,590 plf                  | 1,820 plf\n15/32\" or 1/2\" | 2\"                | 2,175 plf                  | 2,570 plf (blocked only)\n\nCONVERSION TO ASD DESIGN VALUES\nFor ASD design: Allowable unit shear (vs) = Nominal / 2.0\nExample: 7/16\" OSB, 6\" edge nailing → vs = 730 / 2.0 = 365 plf (seismic ASD)\n\nFor LRFD design: Factored unit shear = Nominal × φD = Nominal × 0.80\nExample: 7/16\" OSB, 6\" edge nailing → Factored = 730 × 0.80 = 584 plf (seismic LRFD)\n\nADJUSTMENT FACTORS FOR ASD DESIGN\n1. Species Factor (Cs): For lumber species other than DF-L or Southern Pine, apply species factor from SDPWS Table 4.3A footnotes.\n   - Hem-Fir: Cs = 0.92 (effectively 8% reduction)\n   - Spruce-Pine-Fir: Cs = 0.87 (13% reduction)\n   - All Douglas Fir-Larch and Southern Pine: Cs = 1.0\n\n2. Nail Size: SDPWS Table 4.3A is based on 8d common nails (0.131\" diameter x 2.5\" length) for panels ≤ 1/2\" thick. For 15/32\" or 1/2\" panels with 10d common nails, capacity is increased (see table footnotes).\n\n3. Framing Size: Minimum 3x framing (or 2x blocked) at adjoining panel edges for nail spacings of 3\" and 2\". Single 2x framing is NOT permitted at adjoining panel edges for spacings ≤ 3\".\n\n4. Blocked vs. Unblocked: Values above are for blocked walls (horizontal blocking at all panel edges). Unblocked walls have significantly reduced capacity and are only permitted for specific configurations — use SDPWS Table 4.3C.\n\nDESIGN PROCEDURE\n\nStep 1 — Determine Design Lateral Loads\nFrom structural analysis (tributary area, ASCE 7-22 seismic or wind provisions):\n- Seismic: Fx at each level from equivalent lateral force procedure or modal analysis\n- Wind: Wall pressure × tributary wall area\n\nStep 2 — Select Shear Wall Length\nMaximum unit shear demand:\nv = V_story / (sum of Lw,i)\nWhere V_story = total story shear at level being designed, Lw,i = length of individual shear wall segments.\n\nAspect ratio limits per SDPWS Section 4.3.4:\n- Maximum h/b = 3.5:1 for blocked shear walls (h = wall height, b = wall width)\n- For 2:1 < h/b ≤ 3.5:1, apply reduction factor Cb = (1 + h/b) / 5\n- Do not use wall segments with h/b > 3.5:1 as shear walls\n\nStep 3 — Select Sheathing and Nailing Pattern\nSelect sheathing thickness and nail spacing from table above such that:\nvs (allowable) ≥ v (demand) × applicable adjustment factors\n\nStep 4 — Design Boundary Elements (Chords and Holdowns)\nChord Force at shear wall end posts:\nT = C = (V × h) / Lw\nWhere V = shear wall shear force (lbs), h = wall height (ft), Lw = wall length (ft).\n\nFor seismic loading: Net uplift = T - 0.9D (gravity dead load)\nFor wind loading: Net uplift = T - 0.6D (gravity dead load)\n\nSelect holdown connector per Holdown Selection Matrix (ghm_004) using this net uplift value.\nCompression post must be checked for gravity loads plus chord compression force.\n\nStep 5 — Design Sill Plate Anchorage\nAnchor bolt spacing per Foundation Anchor Bolt Spacing (ghm_005) based on unit shear demand v.\n\nStep 6 — Check Wall Deflection (SDPWS Section 4.3.2)\nShear wall deflection formula (SDPWS Equation 4.3-1):\nδsw = (8vh³)/(EAb) + (vh)/(Gt) + 0.75hen + (da)(h/b)\n\nWhere:\nE = 1,700,000 psi (modulus of elasticity of end posts)\nA = cross-sectional area of end post (in²)\nb = shear wall width (ft)\nh = shear wall height (ft)\nv = unit shear (plf)\nG = panel shear modulus (psi) from SDPWS Table 4.3A footnote (e.g., 90,000 psi for 7/16\" OSB)\nt = effective panel thickness (in)\nen = nail slip (in) from SDPWS Table 4.3C based on nail size and shear demand\nda = holdown anchor displacement/slip (in) per connector manufacturer's data\n\nDrift limit check: δsw ≤ h/240 for wind; δsw ≤ Cd × δallow per ASCE 7-22 Table 12.12-1 for seismic (where Cd = deflection amplification factor for the structural system).\n\nSEISMIC FORCE-RESISTING SYSTEM DESIGNATIONS\nPer ASCE 7-22 Table 12.2-1:\n- Wood light frame shear walls with WSP panels: R = 6.5, Ω₀ = 3.0, Cd = 4.0 for buildings ≤ 65 ft in SDC D, E, F\n- Special wood moment frames: R = 5.5\n- Light frame shear walls with wood structural panels — Risk Category I, ≤ 35 ft in SDC D, E, F: R = 6.5\n\nCOMMON DETAILING REQUIREMENTS\n- Boundary nailing: At panel edges on all boundaries (top plates, bottom plates, chords), minimum 3\" edge distance for nail to stud edge, 3/4\" edge distance to panel edge.\n- Panel orientation: Long dimension of panel parallel to studs (vertical) is standard; horizontal orientation requires additional blocking.\n- Continuous load path: All shear walls must have continuous connections from roof diaphragm to foundation. Verify straps, clips, and connections at each floor level — do not assume gravity connections provide adequate shear transfer.\n- Stagger panel joints: Adjacent WSP panels should be offset minimum 1 stud spacing to reduce continuous joint through wall height.",
