    "memory_id": "ghm_009",
    "title": "Masonry Anchor Design Guide — TMS 402 requirements",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`Masonry Anchor Design Guide — TMS 402-22 and ACI 530 Requirements\n\nOVERVIEW\nAnchors embedded in masonry (concrete masonry units — CMU, and clay brick masonry) must be designed in accordance with TMS 402-22 (Building Code Requirements and Specification for Masonry Structures), which replaced the older ACI 530/ASCE 5/TMS 402 trilogy. This guide covers anchor bolt design for both headed and bent-bar anchor bolts in grouted masonry.\n\nSCOPE OF TMS 402-22 CHAPTER 3 (ANCHOR BOLTS)\nTMS 402-22 Chapter 3 governs headed anchor bolts and bent-bar anchor bolts embedded in masonry. \"Post-installed\" anchors (drilled and epoxied) are covered by ICC-ES evaluation reports and ACI 318 Chapter 17 methodology when embedded in grout, not by TMS 402-22 directly.\n\nANCHOR BOLT TYPES\n\nHeaded Anchor Bolts (TMS 402-22 Section 3.1.5):\nStandard hex-head bolts or threaded rods with nut and washer set in wet grout before masonry hardening. This is the most common type for masonry sill plates, ledgers, and attachment of steel to masonry.\n\nBent-Bar Anchor Bolts (J-bolts and L-bolts):\nJ-bolt or L-bolt: Hook bent at 90° or 180°. Lower tensile capacity than headed bolts because hook can straighten under load. Typically used for lighter-duty applications (sill plates in low-seismic regions).\nMinimum bend: Hook must have inside diameter ≥ 3 × bolt diameter.\n\nMINIMUM INSTALLATION REQUIREMENTS (TMS 402-22 Section 3.1.5)\n\nMinimum embedment depth (lb):\n- Headed bolts: lb ≥ 4db (4 × bolt diameter) or 2 in, whichever is greater\n- Bent-bar bolts: lb ≥ 4db or 2 in, whichever is greater (measured to end of hook)\n- For high-load applications, lb = 12db to 16db commonly used to maximize capacity\n\nMinimum edge distance (lbe):\n- Minimum: 1.5 in measured from center of bolt to face of masonry\n- For masonry cells: center bolt in cell; minimum 1.25db from cell wall\n\nMinimum bolt spacing (s):\n- Adjacent bolts: 4db minimum center-to-center\n- Adjacent to reinforcement: 1.5 in clear from any reinforcing bar\n\nGrout requirements: CMU cell containing anchor bolt must be fully grouted (no partial or face-shell grouting). Grout must have minimum f'm = 1,500 psi compressive strength (often 2,000 psi specified). Do not place anchor in cell without confirming cell is grouted.\n\nDESIGN STRENGTHS — TMS 402-22 SECTION 3.3 (STRENGTH DESIGN)\n\nAxial Tension (Pullout) Strength:\nConcrete breakout controls for shallow embedment:\nBan = 4 × Apt × sqrt(f'm)\nWhere Apt = projected tension breakout area = π × lb² (for single bolt far from edges)\n\nMasonry breakout capacity for single headed bolt (far from edges, f'm = 2,000 psi):\nlb = 4\" embedment: Ban = 4 × π(4²) × sqrt(2,000) = 4 × 50.3 × 44.7 ≈ 8,990 lbs\nlb = 6\" embedment: Ban = 4 × π(6²) × sqrt(2,000) ≈ 20,200 lbs\nlb = 8\" embedment: Ban = 4 × π(8²) × sqrt(2,000) ≈ 35,900 lbs\nlb = 12\" embedment: Ban = 4 × π(12²) × sqrt(2,000) ≈ 80,800 lbs\n\nNote: These are nominal strengths. Apply φ = 0.50 for strength reduction (TMS 402 Section 3.3.1.2).\nDesign tension: φBan = 0.50 × Ban\n\nPryout/Breakout at Edge (TMS 402-22 Section 3.3.2.2):\nWhen bolt is close to edge (lbe < lb):\nProjected area is reduced. Apt,edge = portion of breakout cone not truncated by masonry edge.\nReduction factor = Apt,edge / Apt_full. Apply to Ban.\n\nSteel Tensile Strength:\nBns = Ab × f'ult (where Ab = bolt cross-sectional area, f'ult = specified tensile strength)\n- A307 (Grade 2): f'ult = 60 ksi; A193 B7 (all-thread rod): f'ult = 125 ksi\n- φBns = 0.90 × Bns\n\nGoverning tension: φBn = min(φBan, φBns, φBapn where applicable)\n\nSHEAR STRENGTH — TMS 402-22 SECTION 3.3.3\n\nMasonry Breakout in Shear:\nBvn = 4.0 × Apv × sqrt(f'm)\nWhere Apv = projected shear breakout area = 2.5lbe² (for single bolt)\n\nExample: 5/8\" bolt, lbe = 3\" (edge distance), f'm = 2,000 psi:\nBvn = 4.0 × 2.5(3²) × sqrt(2,000) = 4.0 × 22.5 × 44.7 ≈ 4,020 lbs nominal\nφBvn = 0.60 × 4,020 = 2,412 lbs design\n\nMasonry Crushing (pryout):\nFor bolts farther from edge (shear applied toward the free edge), pryout controls:\nBvn = 4.0 × 1.5lbe² × sqrt(f'm) — same area formula but bolt forces masonry toward edge\n\nSteel Shear Strength:\nBvs = 0.6 × Ab × f'ult\nφBvs = 0.65 × Bvs\n\nCOMBINED TENSION AND SHEAR (TMS 402-22 Section 3.3.4)\nInteraction equation (linear — conservative):\n(bu / φBn) + (bv / φBv) ≤ 1.0\nWhere bu = factored tension demand, bv = factored shear demand.\n\nALLOWABLE STRESS DESIGN (TMS 402-22 SECTION 3.2)\nFor projects using ASD methodology:\nAllowable axial tension (Ba):\nBa = 0.5 × Ban / 2.5 = 0.2 × Ban (divide strength by 2.5 safety factor; Ba limited to lesser of masonry breakout and steel yield)\nFor headed bolt, lb = 8\", f'm = 2,000 psi:\nBan = 35,900 lbs → Ba = 0.2 × 35,900 = 7,180 lbs (but check steel: 0.6 × Ab × Fy governs for small bolt diameters)\n\nAllowable shear (Bv):\nBv = 0.6 × Bvn / 2.5 = 0.24 × Bvn\n\nASD DESIGN VALUES — COMMON ANCHOR SIZES IN MASONRY (f'm = 2,000 psi, Fully Grouted CMU)\nThese are per TMS 402-22 ASD, headed bolts, lb = 8\", far from edges (lbe ≥ 8\"):\n\nBolt Diameter | A307 Steel (ft-kips) | Masonry Breakout (allowable) | Governs\n1/2\"         | Ba_steel = 3.5 kips  | Ba_masonry = 7.2 kips       | Steel\n5/8\"         | Ba_steel = 5.4 kips  | Ba_masonry = 7.2 kips       | Steel\n3/4\"         | Ba_steel = 7.8 kips  | Ba_masonry = 7.2 kips       | Masonry\n7/8\"         | Ba_steel = 10.5 kips | Ba_masonry = 7.2 kips       | Masonry\n1\"           | Ba_steel = 13.9 kips | Ba_masonry = 7.2 kips       | Masonry\n1\" (lb=12\")  | Ba_steel = 13.9 kips | Ba_masonry = 16.2 kips      | Steel (for A307)\n1\" (lb=16\")  | Ba_steel = 13.9 kips | Ba_masonry = 28.8 kips      | Steel governs\n\nFor higher tension: Increase embedment depth; use higher-strength threaded rod (A193 B7); increase grout strength; or use group of smaller bolts.\n\nSPECIAL INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS\nIBC Section 1705.4 requires special inspection for:\n- Anchor bolts set in masonry during construction\n- Post-installed anchors in masonry (continuous inspection)\nTasks: Verify anchor size, embedment depth, position relative to edge and other anchors, cell grouted solid, grout strength (compressive test cylinders), and hook geometry for bent-bar anchors.\n\nPOST-INSTALLED ANCHORS IN MASONRY\nICC-ES AC58 and AC01 anchors tested in concrete may not be used in masonry without masonry-specific testing. Look for ESRs that explicitly list masonry as an approved substrate. Example: Hilti HIT-RE 500 (ESR-3814) lists both concrete and masonry (CMU) as approved substrates. Verify grouting requirements in ESR — most post-installed anchors in masonry require fully grouted cells with minimum grout compressive strength.",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
