    "memory_id": "ghm_010",
    "title": "Cold-Formed Steel Framing Compliance — AISI S100 reference",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`Cold-Formed Steel Framing Compliance — AISI S100-16 (with S2-20 Supplement) Reference Guide\n\nOVERVIEW\nCold-formed steel (CFS) framing uses thin-gauge steel members (18 gauge through 12 gauge, typically) formed by pressing or rolling at room temperature. CFS framing is governed by AISI S100-16 (North American Specification for the Design of Cold-Formed Steel Structural Members) with the 2020 Supplement, and by the following companion standards:\n- AISI S200-12 (North American Standard for Cold-Formed Steel Framing — General Provisions)\n- AISI S210-12 (Floor and Roof System Design)\n- AISI S211-12 (Wall Stud Design)\n- AISI S212-12 (Header Design)\n- AISI S213-07 (Lateral Design — Shear Walls and Diaphragms)\n- AISI S214-12 (Truss Design)\n- AISI S240-15 (North American Standard for Cold-Formed Steel Structural Framing)\n- AISI S400-15 (North American Standard for Seismic Design of Cold-Formed Steel Structural Systems)\n\nIBC 2021 references AISI S100-16 (S2-20) and AISI S240-15 for CFS framing design. Always verify local jurisdiction amendments.\n\nMATERIAL STANDARDS AND GRADES\n\nCommon CFS grades (ASTM):\n- ASTM A1003/A1003M: Standard CFS framing steel, Grades ST33H, ST37H, ST40H, ST50H, ST55H\n  - ST33H: Fy = 33 ksi, Fu = 45 ksi (most common for non-structural tracks)\n  - ST50H: Fy = 50 ksi, Fu = 65 ksi (structural studs and joists)\n  - ST55H: Fy = 55 ksi, Fu = 70 ksi (high-strength structural applications)\n- ASTM A653/A653M: Hot-dipped galvanized sheet, Grade SS33, SS40, SS50, SS80\n  - SS50: Fy = 50 ksi, Fu = 65 ksi — very common for structural CFS members\n\nCoating requirements (corrosion protection):\n- Interior dry conditions: G40 (0.40 oz/ft² zinc, minimum) — most non-structural interior framing\n- Exterior or wet conditions: G60 (0.60 oz/ft²) or G90 (0.90 oz/ft²)\n- Coastal/severe exposure: G90 or aluminum-zinc alloy (AZ50)\nVerify with manufacturer as ICC-ES ESRs for specific products may require minimum coating weights.\n\nSECTION PROPERTIES — COMMON CFS FRAMING MEMBERS\n\nStandard C-stud designations follow SSMA (Steel Stud Manufacturers Association) format:\n[Web Depth in thousandths of inch]-[Section Type]-[Flange Width in thousandths]-[Thickness in mils/gauge]\nExample: 600S162-54 = 6\" deep stud, 1-5/8\" flanges, 54-mil (16 gauge, ~0.0540\") thickness\n\nCommon Stud Sizes and Structural Properties (Grade 50, Fy = 50 ksi):\n\n3-5/8\" (3.625\") C-Stud:\n362S162-33 (20 ga): Ix = 0.232 in⁴, Sx = 0.128 in³, Ag = 0.397 in²\n362S162-43 (18 ga): Ix = 0.293 in⁴, Sx = 0.162 in³, Ag = 0.520 in²\n362S162-54 (16 ga): Ix = 0.366 in⁴, Sx = 0.202 in³, Ag = 0.648 in²\n\n6\" (6.0\") C-Stud:\n600S162-33 (20 ga): Ix = 1.125 in⁴, Sx = 0.375 in³, Ag = 0.618 in²\n600S162-43 (18 ga): Ix = 1.411 in⁴, Sx = 0.470 in³, Ag = 0.810 in²\n600S162-54 (16 ga): Ix = 1.763 in⁴, Sx = 0.588 in³, Ag = 1.012 in²\n600S162-68 (14 ga): Ix = 2.182 in⁴, Sx = 0.727 in³, Ag = 1.289 in²\n\n8\" (8.0\") C-Stud:\n800S162-54 (16 ga): Ix = 3.831 in⁴, Sx = 0.958 in³, Ag = 1.163 in²\n800S162-68 (14 ga): Ix = 4.863 in⁴, Sx = 1.216 in³, Ag = 1.476 in²\n800S162-97 (12 ga): Ix = 6.788 in⁴, Sx = 1.697 in³, Ag = 2.088 in²\n\nNote: Properties above are gross section properties. Effective section properties (Se, Ae) used for design are reduced below these due to local buckling — compute per AISI S100 Chapter B or use manufacturer design tables.\n\nDESIGN METHODOLOGY — AISI S100-16\n\nDirect Strength Method (DSM — Appendix 1, now Chapter F in S100-16):\nDSM is the preferred method per AISI S100-16. Computes strength by directly checking buckling modes:\n1. Local buckling (Mncr_l, Pncr_l)\n2. Distortional buckling (Mncr_d, Pncr_d)\n3. Global (Euler/lateral-torsional) buckling\n\nCUFSM (Cornell University Finite Strip Method) software or AISI Design Guide tables are used to compute critical elastic buckling loads for DSM.\n\nEffective Width Method (EWM — Main Spec Chapters B through E):\nTraditional method. Computes reduced flange and web effective widths due to local buckling, then uses reduced section properties for strength calculation. More conservative and more labor-intensive than DSM.\n\nWALL STUD DESIGN (AISI S211-12 and S100-16)\nFor axial load (bearing wall studs), key limit states:\n1. Flexural buckling about weak axis (y-y): Pne = Ag × Fn, where Fn is based on KyLy/ry (K = 1.0 for pin-pin ends; can use K = 0.65 if bridging provides lateral restraint at third points)\n2. Flexural-torsional buckling: Critical for open sections — compute using AISI S100 Section C4.1\n3. Local/distortional buckling interaction with global buckling: Per DSM Section 1.2.1.2\n\nBridging requirements (AISI S211): Studs with h/t > 200 (web slenderness) require horizontal bridging at regular intervals to prevent web distortion. Maximum bridging spacing typically limited to L/3 or 8 ft, whichever is less.\n\nSHEAR WALL DESIGN — AISI S213-07 AND S400-15\nFor CFS-framed shear walls with steel sheet or WSP sheathing:\n\nSteel sheet sheathed shear walls (AISI S213 Table B1):\n- 33-mil (20 ga) steel sheet, 6\" edge fasteners: vs = 763 plf (seismic, ASD)\n- 43-mil (18 ga) steel sheet, 6\" edge fasteners: vs = 1,060 plf (seismic, ASD)\n- 54-mil (16 ga) steel sheet, 4\" edge fasteners: vs = 1,750 plf (seismic, ASD)\n\nWood structural panel (OSB/plywood) on CFS framing (AISI S213 Table B2):\n- 7/16\" OSB, #8 screws at 6\" o.c. edges: vs = 780 plf (seismic, ASD)\n- 7/16\" OSB, #8 screws at 4\" o.c. edges: vs = 1,020 plf (seismic, ASD)\n- 15/32\" plywood, #8 screws at 3\" o.c. edges: vs = 1,330 plf (seismic, ASD)\n\nFASTENER REQUIREMENTS FOR CFS\nScrew types (AISI S200-12 Section C1):\n- #8 (0.164\" diameter): Standard for connecting CFS to CFS framing (stud to track)\n- #10 (0.190\" diameter): For attaching sheathing to thicker (≥ 54-mil) framing\n- #12 (0.216\" diameter): Heavy-duty CFS-to-CFS connections in thick members\n\nScrew penetration: Minimum 3 exposed threads beyond the connected material. For sheathing screws: screw point must pass through CFS framing with 3 threads exposed.\n\nCritical screw pullover (head pull-through): Checked per AISI S100 Section E4.4.1. Common failure mode for thin-gauge steel (33–43 mil) with large-diameter screws.\n\nCFS SEISMIC DESIGN — AISI S400-15\nSpecial CFS Moment Frames (SCMSF), Special CFS Shear Walls, and other seismic systems per AISI S400-15:\n- For SDC D, E, F: Only AISI S400-approved systems permitted in SFRS\n- R-values: CFS-framed shear walls with steel sheathing: R = 6.5; with wood sheathing: R = 6.5\n- Capacity-based design: Chord studs designed for amplified (Ω₀) loads\n- Framing designator (HDR) for chord framing: Higher gage (54 mil or thicker) to prevent local crippling at shear wall ends\n\nSPECIAL INSPECTION FOR CFS\nPer IBC Section 1705.11, special inspection required for:\n- CFS framing for buildings in SDC D, E, F\n- Structural cold-formed steel welding (fillet welds to gusset plates, etc.)\nPeriodic inspection: Verify member sizes, gauges, spacing, fastener type and spacing, connection details match approved drawings.",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
    "tags": [
      "cold-formed-steel",
      "cfs",
      "aisi-s100",
      "framing",
      "stud",
      "shear-wall",
      "seismic",
      "aisi-s400",
      "direct-strength-method",
      "wall-framing"
    ]
