    "memory_id": "ghm_012",
    "title": "Multi-Story Wood Frame Lateral Design — Up to 5 Stories",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`MULTI-STORY WOOD FRAME LATERAL DESIGN — UP TO 5 STORIES\n\nINTRODUCTION\nThe construction of multi-story wood-frame buildings (often called \"5-over-1\" or \"4-over-1\" when combined with a concrete podium) has become prevalent for residential and mixed-use projects. This guide addresses the lateral force-resisting system (LFRS) design considerations, code basis, and common engineering practices for wood-frame buildings up to five stories.\n\nCODE BASIS\n- IBC 2021 / CBC 2022 Chapter 23: Wood construction\n- SDPWS 2021 (Special Design Provisions for Wind and Seismic): Primary reference for shear wall and diaphragm design\n- AWC NDS 2018: Connection and member design\n- ASCE 7-22: Seismic and wind load determination\n- IBC Table 601: Type III-A construction allows up to 5 stories; Type V-A allows up to 4 stories above a podium\n\nSEISMIC DESIGN CATEGORIES AND WOOD SHEAR WALLS\nIBC Table 1613 / ASCE 7-22 Chapter 11 establishes Seismic Design Categories (SDC) A through F.\n\nFor wood-frame shear walls, SDPWS Table 4.3A provides allowable unit shear capacities (v) in pounds per linear foot (plf) for structural panels (OSB or plywood):\n\nCommon shear wall configurations:\n- 3/8\" OSB, 8d nails at 6\" o.c. edge / 12\" field: ~260 plf (ASD)\n- 15/32\" OSB, 10d nails at 4\" o.c. edge / 12\" field: ~490 plf (ASD)\n- 15/32\" OSB, 10d nails at 2\" o.c. edge / 12\" field: ~770 plf (ASD)\n- Double 15/32\" OSB with 10d nails at 2\" o.c. each panel: ~1540 plf (ASD)\n\nSDPWS Section 4.3.3: Aspect ratio limits for shear walls\n- Maximum h/b ratio: 3.5:1 for blocked shear walls (with reduction factor for 2:1 to 3.5:1)\n- For h/b > 2:1, apply Cs = (2b/h)^0.5 reduction factor (SDPWS Eq. 4.3-1)\n- Minimum wall length: 24\" for SDC D, E, F per IBC 2305.3\n\nSHEAR WALL OVERTURNING AND HOLD-DOWNS\nFor multi-story buildings, overturning forces accumulate through each story. The net tension load on a hold-down at any given level is:\n\nT = M_OT / L_wall − 0.9 * W_dead (for LRFD) or T = M_OT / L_wall − 0.6 * W_dead (for ASD with ASCE 7 load combinations)\n\nWhere M_OT is the cumulative overturning moment from all stories above.\n\nContinuous rod tie-down systems (e.g., Simpson Strong-Tie Strong-Rod, Hilti MDI):\n- Preferred for 3+ story wood frame buildings\n- Rod diameter typically 1\" to 1.25\" for moderate loads; 1.5\" to 2\" for high seismic zones\n- Shrinkage compensating devices (take-up devices) are REQUIRED to account for wood shrinkage and elastic elongation — see SDPWS Commentary and ICC-ES reports for specific products\n\nSTORY DRIFT AND DEFLECTION\nSDPWS Section 4.3.2 provides the four-term deflection formula for wood shear walls:\n\ndelta_sw = (8vh^3)/(EAb) + (vh)/(Gt) + (h*d_a)/b + h_n\n\nWhere:\n- v = unit shear (plf)\n- h = wall height (in)\n- E = modulus of elasticity of chord members (psi)\n- A = area of chord cross-section (in^2)\n- b = wall length (in)\n- G = shear modulus of sheathing (psi)\n- t = effective sheathing thickness (in)\n- d_a = vertical deformation of hold-down assembly (in) — critical for multi-story\n- h_n = nail slip (in) per SDPWS Table 4.3B\n\nASCE 7 Table 12.12-1: Maximum allowable story drift\n- Risk Category I/II: 0.025 * h_sx (residential)\n- Risk Category III: 0.020 * h_sx\n- Risk Category IV: 0.015 * h_sx\n\nDIAPHRAGM DESIGN — WOOD STRUCTURAL PANELS\nSDPWS Table 4.2A: Blocked diaphragm capacities (simplified):\n- 15/32\" OSB, 10d at 6\" boundary/4\" other edges: ~480 plf\n- 15/32\" OSB, 10d at 4\" all edges: ~640 plf\n\nDiaphragm flexibility classification (SDPWS Section 4.2.5):\n- Wood diaphragms are PRESUMED flexible unless enveloped by concrete topping slab or calculations demonstrate rigidity\n- Flexible diaphragm: distribute loads to walls by tributary area\n- Rigid diaphragm: distribute loads to walls by relative stiffness\n\nCONSTRUCTION TYPE AND BUILDING HEIGHT LIMITS\nIBC Table 504.3 (sprinklered):\n- Type III-A: 5 stories / 65 feet\n- Type III-B: 4 stories / 55 feet\n- Type V-A: 4 stories / 50 feet (5 stories with sprinklers per CBC modifications)\n- Type V-B: 3 stories / 40 feet\n\nPODIUM CONSTRUCTION (5-OVER-1)\nA concrete or post-tensioned concrete podium (Type I-A or I-B construction) at the ground level allows additional stories above:\n- Transfer deck must be designed for vertical loads and overturning from wood frame above\n- Seismic mass distribution must account for the stiff concrete podium beneath flexible wood frame\n- IBC Section 403.3.2: Podium height does not count toward wood frame story count in many jurisdictions (verify AHJ)\n\nSPECIAL INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS (IBC 1705.12)\nFor SDC C through F:\n- Nailing of shear panels: Required for high-load shear walls\n- Hold-down anchor bolt installation\n- Shear transfer connections (drag struts, collectors)\n- Continuous rod tie-down systems — verify rod tensioning where required\n\nDESIGN CHECKLIST FOR MULTI-STORY WOOD FRAME\n[ ] Lateral system clearly identified on drawings (shear wall schedule, location plan)\n[ ] Shear wall capacities calculated per SDPWS\n[ ] Aspect ratio limits checked for each wall\n[ ] Overturning and hold-down forces calculated for each story\n[ ] Continuous rod tie-down system specified and sized\n[ ] Shrinkage compensating devices specified\n[ ] Collector/drag strut design completed\n[ ] Diaphragm boundary nailing shown on framing plan\n[ ] Story drift calculated and compared to ASCE 7 limits\n[ ] Special inspection program included in permit set",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
