    "memory_id": "ghm_013",
    "title": "Concrete Anchor Design per ACI 318 — Appendix D Calculations",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`CONCRETE ANCHOR DESIGN PER ACI 318 — APPENDIX D CALCULATIONS\n\nSCOPE AND CODE REFERENCE\nACI 318-19 Chapter 17 (formerly Appendix D in ACI 318-11 and earlier) governs the design of cast-in-place and post-installed anchors in concrete. This guide covers the strength design method for both tension and shear loading, failure mode hierarchy, and practical calculation procedures.\n\nNote: ACI 318-14 moved Appendix D content into Chapter 17. The calculations are substantially similar; this guide references ACI 318-19 section numbering.\n\nANCHOR TYPES AND DEFINITIONS\nCast-in anchors: Anchor bolts, headed studs, hooked bolts installed before concrete placement\nPost-installed anchors:\n- Expansion anchors (torque-controlled or displacement-controlled)\n- Undercut anchors\n- Adhesive (bonded) anchors — governed by ACI 318-19 Section 17.4.5 and ICC-ES AC308\n\nKEY VARIABLES\n- hef: Effective embedment depth (in)\n- da: Anchor diameter (in)\n- Fy, Futa: Yield and ultimate tensile strength of anchor steel (psi)\n- f'c: Specified compressive strength of concrete (psi)\n- ca1: Edge distance in direction of shear loading (in)\n- ca2: Edge distance perpendicular to shear (in)\n- s: Anchor spacing (in)\n- N_b, V_b: Basic breakout strength of single anchor in tension/shear\n\nTENSION DESIGN — FAILURE MODES (ACI 318-19 Section 17.6)\n\n1. Steel Failure in Tension (17.6.1):\nNsa = Ase,N * futa\nWhere Ase,N = effective cross-sectional area of anchor in tension (in^2)\nPhi factor: phi = 0.75 (ductile steel), 0.65 (brittle steel)\n\n2. Concrete Breakout Failure in Tension (17.6.2):\nFor a single anchor: Ncb = (ANc / ANco) * psi_ed,N * psi_c,N * psi_cp,N * Nb\n\nANco = 9 * hef^2 (projected area of single anchor, no edge effects)\nANc = actual projected cone area (accounts for edge distances and group effects)\n\nBasic breakout strength:\nNb = kc * lambda_a * sqrt(f'c) * hef^1.5\n- kc = 24 for cast-in anchors; 17 for post-installed anchors\n- lambda_a = 1.0 for normalweight concrete; 0.75 for lightweight concrete\n\nEdge modification factor (psi_ed,N):\n- If ca,min >= 1.5 * hef: psi_ed,N = 1.0\n- If ca,min < 1.5 * hef: psi_ed,N = 0.7 + 0.3 * (ca,min / 1.5*hef)\n\nCracking factor (psi_c,N):\n- Uncracked concrete, no supplementary reinforcement: 1.25\n- Cracked concrete, no supplementary reinforcement: 1.0\n- Cracked concrete, hair-wire or edge reinforcement: 1.2\n- Cracked concrete, reinforcement enclosed in stirrups: 1.4\n\n3. Pullout Failure (17.6.3) — Cast-in anchors:\nNpn = psi_c,P * Np\nFor headed anchor: Np = 8 * Abrg * f'c\nWhere Abrg = net bearing area of anchor head (in^2)\n\n4. Side-Face Blowout (17.6.4) — Deep anchors near edges:\nNsb = 160 * sqrt(ca1) * sqrt(Abrg) * lambda_a * sqrt(f'c)\nApplicable when: hef > 2.5 * ca1\n\n5. Bond Failure (Adhesive Anchors, 17.6.5):\nNa = (ANa / ANao) * psi_ed,Na * psi_cp,Na * psi_g,Na * Nba\nNba = tau_uncr * pi * da * hef (uncr.) or tau_cr * pi * da * hef (cr.)\ntau values from ICC-ES evaluation report for specific adhesive product\n\nSHEAR DESIGN — FAILURE MODES (ACI 318-19 Section 17.7)\n\n1. Steel Failure in Shear (17.7.1):\nVsa = Ase,V * 0.6 * futa (standard anchor)\nPhi factor: phi = 0.65\n\n2. Concrete Breakout in Shear (17.7.2):\nFor single anchor: Vcb = (AVc / AVco) * psi_ed,V * psi_c,V * psi_h,V * Vb\n\nAVco = 4.5 * ca1^2\nBasic breakout: Vb = [7 * (le/da)^0.2 * sqrt(da)] * lambda_a * sqrt(f'c) * ca1^1.5\n- le = load-bearing length of anchor for shear (min of hef or 8*da)\n\nEdge factor (psi_ed,V):\n- If ca2 >= 1.5 * ca1: psi_ed,V = 1.0\n- If ca2 < 1.5 * ca1: psi_ed,V = 0.7 + 0.3 * (ca2 / 1.5*ca1)\n\nMember thickness factor (psi_h,V):\n- If ha >= 1.5 * ca1: psi_h,V = 1.0\n- If ha < 1.5 * ca1: psi_h,V = sqrt(1.5*ca1 / ha)\n\n3. Concrete Pryout in Shear (17.7.3):\nVcp = kcp * Ncb\n- kcp = 1.0 for hef < 2.5 in; 2.0 for hef >= 2.5 in\nGoverns for deep anchors loaded in shear near the surface\n\nCOMBINED TENSION AND SHEAR (ACI 318-19 Section 17.8)\nInteraction equation:\n(Nua / phi_Nn)^5/3 + (Vua / phi_Vn)^5/3 <= 1.0\n\nSimplified: if either ratio <= 0.2, the combined check is waived for that component\n\nSEISMIC DESIGN REQUIREMENTS (17.10)\nFor anchors in Seismic Design Category C through F:\n- Anchors must be designed for 1.2 * seismic demand\n- phi factor reduced: phi = 0.75 * 0.75 = 0.5625 for concrete breakout\n- OR anchor must be designed so steel controls (ductile behavior)\n- Post-installed anchors must have ICC-ES evaluation report with seismic qualification per AC193 or AC308\n\nMINIMUM EDGE DISTANCE AND SPACING (17.9)\n- Minimum edge distance: typically 6*da for post-installed; per manufacturer for adhesive\n- Minimum spacing: typically 6*hef\n- Maximum spacing to prevent splitting: depends on anchor type and concrete cover\n\nPRACTICAL DESIGN EXAMPLE\nGiven: 3/4\" diameter A307 cast-in anchor bolt, hef = 8\", f'c = 3000 psi, normalweight concrete, no edge effects, cracked concrete assumed, no supplementary reinforcement\n\nSteel tension: Nsa = Ase * futa = 0.334 in^2 * 60,000 psi = 20,040 lb; phi*Nsa = 0.75 * 20,040 = 15,030 lb\n\nBreakout tension: Nb = 24 * 1.0 * sqrt(3000) * 8^1.5 = 24 * 54.77 * 22.63 = 29,719 lb\nANco = 9 * 64 = 576 in^2; ANc = 576 in^2 (no edge effects); psi_ed,N = 1.0; psi_c,N = 1.0\nNcb = 1.0 * 1.0 * 1.0 * 29,719 = 29,719 lb; phi*Ncb = 0.70 * 29,719 = 20,803 lb\nControls: phi*Nsa = 15,030 lb (steel governs — ductile failure, acceptable)",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
