    "memory_id": "ghm_016",
    "title": "Diaphragm Design for Wood Structures — Flexible vs Rigid",
    "category": "construction_compliance",
    "content": "`DIAPHRAGM DESIGN FOR WOOD STRUCTURES — FLEXIBLE VS RIGID\n\nINTRODUCTION\nThe horizontal diaphragm is the element that collects and distributes lateral forces (seismic and wind) to the vertical lateral force-resisting elements (shear walls or frames). Understanding the behavior classification — flexible or rigid — is fundamental because it determines how loads are distributed to the supporting shear walls.\n\nCODE AND DESIGN REFERENCES\n- ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3: Diaphragm flexibility classification\n- SDPWS 2021 Section 4.2: Wood structural panel diaphragm design\n- SDPWS Tables 4.2A, 4.2B, 4.2C: Allowable unit shear capacities\n- IBC 2021 Section 2305: General design requirements for lateral force-resisting systems in wood structures\n\nDIAPHRAGM FLEXIBILITY CLASSIFICATION (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.1)\n\nIdealized Flexible Diaphragm (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.1.1):\nA diaphragm may be idealized as flexible when ANY of these conditions apply:\na. Unreinforced masonry shear walls\nb. The diaphragm is constructed with:\n   - Wood structural panels (OSB/plywood) WITHOUT a composite concrete topping\n   - Untopped steel deck\n   And the structure is not of concrete or masonry construction\n\nCRITICAL: For light wood-frame buildings with wood structural panel diaphragms and wood shear walls, ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.1.1(2) PRESUMES flexibility — no calculation needed. The engineer simply distributes loads by tributary area.\n\nIdealized Rigid Diaphragm (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.1.2):\nDiaphragms of concrete slabs (with or without topping) may be idealized as rigid when:\n- The diaphragm's span-to-depth ratio is 3:1 or less\n- No horizontal irregularity per ASCE 7-22 Table 12.3-1 is present\n\nCalculated Flexible Diaphragm (ASCE 7-22 Section 12.3.1.3):\nWhen neither idealized condition applies, perform the calculation:\n- Delta_MDD: Maximum in-plane diaphragm deflection under lateral load\n- Delta_ADVE: Average drift of the vertical elements (shear walls) at both ends\n\nIf Delta_MDD > 2 * Delta_ADVE: Diaphragm is flexible\nIf Delta_MDD <= 2 * Delta_ADVE: Diaphragm is rigid\n\nLOAD DISTRIBUTION METHODS\n\nFlexible Diaphragm — Tributary Area Method:\nEach shear wall receives a load proportional to the tributary floor/roof area it supports. This is analogous to simply-supported beams between supports.\n\nExample: 60-foot building with shear walls at each end and one interior wall at 40 feet from the left end. Wind load = 500 plf along the building.\n- Left wall tributary width: 20 ft | Load to left wall = 500 * 20 = 10,000 lb\n- Interior wall tributary width: 20 ft (half of 40 ft) + 10 ft (half of 20 ft) = 30 ft | Load = 15,000 lb\n- Right wall: 10 ft | Load = 5,000 lb\n\nRigid Diaphragm — Relative Stiffness Method:\nLoads are distributed to walls based on their relative lateral stiffness plus any torsional effects. This requires calculating each wall's stiffness k_i.\n\nWall stiffness for wood shear walls (simplified):\nk = G_a * L / H (for rigid rotation), or calculated per SDPWS deflection formula\nWhere G_a = apparent shear wall stiffness (from SDPWS Table 4.3A commentary)\n\nCenter of Rigidity (CR) and Center of Mass (CM):\nCR_x = Sum(k_yi * x_i) / Sum(k_yi)\nWhere k_yi = stiffness of walls resisting forces in y-direction\n\nTorsional Eccentricity:\ne_x = x_CM - x_CR (eccentricity between center of mass and center of rigidity)\nASCE 7-22 Section 12.8.4.2: Accidental torsion requires shifting CM by +/- 5% of the diaphragm dimension\n\nDirect shear to each wall: V_di = V * k_i / Sum(k_i)\nTorsional shear: V_ti = +/- (V * e + V * 0.05L) * k_i * d_i / Sum(k_i * d_i^2)\nTotal wall force: V_i = V_di + V_ti (worst sign combination)\n\nWOOD STRUCTURAL PANEL DIAPHRAGM DESIGN\n\nSDPWS Table 4.2A — Blocked Diaphragm Capacities (Allowable Unit Shear, ASD):\nSelected values for OSB Structural Panel Grade (3-ply minimum):\nPanel   | Nail Size | Nail Spacing at Boundaries/Continuous Panel Edges | Capacity\n15/32\"  |   10d     |    6\" / 6\" (all edges)                            | 340 plf\n15/32\"  |   10d     |    4\" / 4\" (all edges)                            | 480 plf\n15/32\"  |   10d     |    2.5\" / 2.5\" (all edges)                        | 640 plf\n19/32\"  |   10d     |    2\" / 3\"                                         | 820 plf\n(Note: Adjust by load duration factor CD = 1.6 for seismic; CD = 1.6 for wind)\n\nSDPWS Table 4.2C — Unblocked Diaphragm Capacities:\nUnblocked diaphragms have reduced capacity and are generally not suitable for high-seismic applications.\n- 15/32\" OSB, 10d at 6\" perimeter: 185 plf (unblocked)\n\nBLOCKING REQUIREMENTS\nSDPWS Section 4.2.7: Diaphragm blocking at panel edges is required when:\n- Panel edges are not supported by framing\n- Capacity exceeds unblocked values\n\nBlocking orientation: Perpendicular to the direction of load transfer (parallel to the span direction usually requires blocking at mid-span panel edges)\n\nBOUNDARY MEMBERS (CHORDS AND COLLECTORS)\n\nChord Forces:\nDiaphragm chords resist the tension and compression couple from bending of the diaphragm treated as a deep beam.\nT = C = M / d = (w * L^2 / 8) / d\nWhere w = lateral load (plf), L = diaphragm span, d = diaphragm depth\n\nFor wood diaphragms, chords are typically doubled top plates or LVL members running continuously along the perimeter walls.\n\nCollector (Drag Strut) Forces:\nWhen shear walls do not extend the full length of the diaphragm, collectors drag the diaphragm shear to the shear wall boundaries.\nCollector force diagram: Add diaphragm unit shear across the opening region to find peak collector force.\nConnection requirements: Collectors must be positively connected to transfer accumulated forces — multiple nailing patterns and/or metalconnectors required at high loads.\n\nDIAPHRAGM DEFLECTION (SDPWS SECTION 4.2.2)\nThree-term deflection formula for blocked diaphragms:\ndelta_D = (5vL^3) / (8EAW) + vL / (4Gt) + 0.188 * L * en\n\nWhere:\n- v = maximum shear in diaphragm (plf)\n- L = diaphragm span (ft)\n- E = modulus of elasticity of chord (psi)\n- A = area of chord member (in^2)\n- W = diaphragm width (ft)\n- G = shear modulus of panel (psi)\n- t = effective sheathing thickness (in)\n- en = nail deformation per SDPWS Table 4.2D\n\nHORIZONTAL IRREGULARITIES (ASCE 7-22 TABLE 12.3-1)\nIrregularities that trigger additional design requirements:\n- Type 1a/1b: Torsional irregularity (Max story drift > 1.2 or 1.4 times average)\n- Type 3: Diaphragm discontinuity (opening > 50% of gross area or stiffness change > 50%)\n- Type 4: Out-of-plane offset\n- Type 5: Nonparallel systems\n\nFor SDC D, E, F: Type 1a/1b and 4 require dynamic analysis for SDC D+ with Type 5 or 3 irregularities.",
