    "memory_id": "ghm_021",
    "title": "EU AI Act Article 17 Compliance Checklist",
    "category": "ai_compliance",
    "content": "`EU AI Act Article 17 establishes quality management system requirements for providers of high-risk AI systems. This checklist covers the mandatory elements organizations must implement before deploying high-risk AI systems in EU markets.\n\nSCOPE AND APPLICABILITY\nArticle 17 applies to all providers placing high-risk AI systems on the EU market or putting them into service. High-risk systems include those in Annex III categories: biometric identification, critical infrastructure management, education, employment, essential private and public services, law enforcement, migration control, administration of justice, and democratic processes.\n\nQUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS\n\n1. Strategy for Regulatory Compliance\n- Document a written strategy describing how the AI system complies with the EU AI Act\n- Assign senior management accountability for AI compliance oversight\n- Establish procedures for monitoring regulatory developments and updating compliance posture\n- Define escalation paths when compliance gaps are identified\n\n2. Techniques and Procedures\n- Implement systematic design and development processes with version control\n- Maintain documented procedures for data management including collection, labeling, validation\n- Establish testing and validation protocols prior to deployment\n- Create procedures for post-market monitoring of deployed systems\n- Document procedures for handling non-conformities and corrective actions\n\n3. Data and Data Governance\n- Implement data governance practices covering training, validation, and test datasets\n- Document data collection and processing methods with justification\n- Maintain records of data provenance, labeling methodologies, and quality assessments\n- Ensure data sets are relevant, sufficiently representative, and free from errors\n- Implement procedures to detect and mitigate bias in training data\n\n4. Technical Documentation\n- Maintain comprehensive technical documentation per Annex IV requirements\n- Include general description of the AI system and its intended purpose\n- Document design specifications, system architecture, and algorithms used\n- Record training methodologies, training datasets, and performance metrics\n- Maintain records of known risks and mitigation measures implemented\n\n5. Record-Keeping and Logging\n- Implement automatic logging capabilities to ensure traceability\n- Retain logs for minimum periods specified by applicable law (generally 6 months for providers)\n- Ensure logs capture system events sufficient for post-hoc reconstruction of incidents\n- Implement access controls protecting log integrity\n\n6. Transparency and User Information Provision\n- Prepare instructions for use compliant with Article 13 transparency requirements\n- Provide clear information about system capabilities and limitations\n- Document foreseeable misuse scenarios and contraindications\n- Include information about human oversight requirements and mechanisms\n\n7. Human Oversight Measures\n- Design systems to allow human operators to understand, monitor, and override AI outputs\n- Implement interfaces enabling human oversight appropriate to the risk level\n- Train personnel on human oversight responsibilities and procedures\n- Document override procedures and their expected outcomes\n\n8. Accuracy, Robustness, and Cybersecurity\n- Achieve and document accuracy levels appropriate to the intended purpose\n- Implement robustness measures against errors, faults, and inconsistencies\n- Address cybersecurity risks proportionate to system criticality\n- Conduct periodic testing to verify maintained performance standards\n\n9. Conformity Assessment\n- Conduct internal conformity assessment OR engage notified body (depending on system category)\n- For general-purpose AI integrated into high-risk systems, document conformity basis\n- Maintain conformity assessment documentation and make available to authorities on request\n- Affix CE marking only after successful conformity assessment\n\n10. Post-Market Monitoring Plan\n- Establish proactive post-market monitoring system collecting user feedback and performance data\n- Define key performance indicators and thresholds triggering corrective action\n- Implement procedures for reporting serious incidents to national authorities\n- Conduct periodic reviews of monitoring data and update risk assessments accordingly\n\nDOCUMENTATION REQUIREMENTS BY TIMELINE\n- Before market placement: Complete technical documentation, conformity assessment, CE marking\n- At market placement: Register in EU AI Act database (for Annex III systems)\n- Ongoing: Maintain logs, conduct post-market monitoring, update documentation for material changes\n- Incident reporting: Notify market surveillance authority within 15 days of serious incidents\n\nENFORCEMENT AND PENALTIES\nNon-compliance penalties under Article 99: up to €30 million or 6% of global annual turnover for violations of prohibited AI practices; up to €20 million or 4% for violations of other obligations including Article 17 quality management requirements. National market surveillance authorities enforce the regulation with investigation and corrective action powers.\n\nPRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION STEPS\n- Conduct AI inventory to identify all high-risk systems in scope\n- Appoint AI compliance officer or designate responsible function\n- Gap-assess current quality management systems against Article 17 requirements\n- Develop remediation roadmap with milestone dates\n- Implement required processes, documentation, and controls\n- Conduct internal audit before deployment\n- Establish ongoing monitoring and review cadence",
    "price_usdc": 0,
