    "memory_id": "ghm_022",
    "title": "US OMB AI Governance Memorandum Summary",
    "category": "ai_compliance",
    "content": "`The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) has issued several memoranda governing federal agency use of artificial intelligence. This summary covers the key requirements from M-24-10 (Advancing Governance, Innovation, and Risk Management for Agency Use of Artificial Intelligence) and related guidance.\n\nOVERVIEW OF OMB AI GOVERNANCE FRAMEWORK\nOMB M-24-10, issued March 2024, established minimum practices for federal agencies using AI in ways that affect rights and safety. It built upon Executive Order 14110 on Safe, Secure, and Trustworthy AI (October 2023) and superseded earlier OMB guidance. The memorandum requires agencies to govern AI use responsibly, advance AI innovation, and manage AI-related risks.\n\nCHIEF AI OFFICER REQUIREMENTS\nEach covered agency must designate a Chief AI Officer (CAIO) who holds primary responsibility for coordinating agency AI use, promoting AI innovation, managing AI-related risks, and ensuring compliance with applicable law. The CAIO must have appropriate expertise and sufficient authority to perform the role, report to the agency head or deputy, and coordinate with the Chief Information Officer, Chief Data Officer, and other relevant officials. Agencies must establish an AI Governance Board or equivalent body chaired by or reporting to the CAIO.\n\nMINIMUM RISK MANAGEMENT PRACTICES FOR RIGHTS AND SAFETY-IMPACTING AI\nAgencies using AI in ways that impact rights (civil rights, civil liberties, equal opportunities, privacy) or safety must implement minimum practices including:\n\nImpact Assessment: Conduct and document assessments of AI use cases identifying risks to rights and safety before deployment. Assessments must consider disparate impacts on protected classes, potential for erroneous outcomes, and cybersecurity risks.\n\nHuman Oversight: Ensure humans can review, audit, correct, and override AI-driven decisions affecting individual rights or safety. Establish clear accountability chains identifying who is responsible for AI outputs. Prohibit fully automated decision-making in specified high-stakes contexts without meaningful human review.\n\nNotice and Explanation: Provide notice to individuals when AI is used to make or inform decisions significantly affecting them. Provide explanations of AI-driven decisions upon request in language understandable to affected parties. Maintain records enabling reconstruction of AI decision processes.\n\nContinuous Monitoring: Monitor deployed AI systems for performance, accuracy, and potential harms. Establish feedback mechanisms for affected individuals and front-line users. Conduct periodic reviews and retire or modify systems that fail to meet performance standards.\n\nDATA GOVERNANCE REQUIREMENTS\nAgencies must implement data governance practices ensuring AI training and operational data is accurate, complete, relevant, and representative. This includes documenting data sources, assessing data quality, implementing controls against biased or unrepresentative data, and ensuring data used in AI systems complies with applicable privacy laws including the Privacy Act of 1974.\n\nTRANSPARENCY AND PUBLIC REPORTING\nAgencies must maintain and publicly post annual inventories of AI use cases. Inventories must identify each AI use case, its purpose, the rights or safety impact determination, and whether minimum practices have been implemented. OMB publishes aggregate reporting on agency AI use case inventories. Agencies must also publish information enabling meaningful public understanding of how consequential AI systems function.\n\nPROCUREMENT REQUIREMENTS\nWhen acquiring AI from vendors, agencies must ensure contracts include provisions for: appropriate testing and evaluation before deployment, ongoing performance monitoring, incident reporting by vendors, rights to audit AI systems, and compliance with applicable federal AI governance requirements. Agencies should prefer AI systems that are explainable, auditable, and that support human oversight requirements.\n\nINNOVATION AND RESPONSIBLE EXPERIMENTATION\nThe memorandum encourages agencies to experiment with and adopt AI to improve government services and operations. Agencies should establish AI sandboxes and pilots with appropriate governance guardrails. The CAIO should facilitate internal AI innovation while ensuring compliance with risk management requirements.\n\nINTERAGENCY COORDINATION\nThe AI Council, chaired by OMB's Deputy Director for Management, coordinates AI governance across agencies. The National AI Initiative Office provides technical assistance. NIST's AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0) serves as the primary voluntary framework agencies use to operationalize risk management practices.\n\nENFORCEMENT AND ACCOUNTABILITY\nOMB monitors agency compliance through annual reporting requirements. Agency CAIOs must certify compliance with minimum practices for rights and safety-impacting AI annually. Non-compliant agencies may face budget and management reviews. Inspectors General have authority to audit agency AI governance programs.\n\nNIST AI RMF ALIGNMENT\nAgencies are expected to align AI governance programs with the NIST AI RMF four core functions: Govern (establish culture, policies, processes), Map (identify AI risks and context), Measure (analyze and assess risks), Manage (prioritize and address risks). The AI RMF provides detailed practices at each function level that agencies can adopt proportionate to their risk profile.\n\nEXECUTIVE ORDER 14110 IMPLEMENTATION\nOMB M-24-10 implements several EO 14110 provisions including requirements for safety evaluations of dual-use foundation models, content authentication measures, AI talent recruitment, and international AI safety cooperation. Agencies with national security missions have additional requirements under separate classified guidance.\n\nPRACTICAL COMPLIANCE STEPS FOR FEDERAL AGENCIES\n1. Designate CAIO with appropriate authority and resources\n2. Establish AI Governance Board with cross-functional representation\n3. Complete AI use case inventory including rights/safety impact assessments\n4. Implement minimum practices for all rights/safety-impacting uses\n5. Update procurement templates and vendor contracts\n6. Establish post-deployment monitoring programs\n7. Train workforce on AI use policies and responsibilities\n8. Publish required public transparency information\n9. Submit annual certification to OMB",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
