    "memory_id": "ghm_023",
    "title": "Singapore MAS AI Governance Framework",
    "category": "ai_compliance",
    "content": "`The Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) has developed one of the world's most comprehensive AI governance frameworks for financial services. This reference covers the MAS Principles to Promote Fairness, Ethics, Accountability and Transparency (FEAT), the Veritas initiative, and related guidance.\n\nMAS FEAT PRINCIPLES OVERVIEW\nThe FEAT Principles, published in November 2018 and updated subsequently, establish expectations for financial institutions (FIs) using AI and data analytics (AIDA) in customer-facing decisions. The principles are organized around four pillars:\n\nFAIRNESS\nFIs must ensure AIDA-driven customer decisions are fair and do not discriminate on protected characteristics. Key requirements:\n- Define fairness metrics appropriate to the use case before deployment\n- Test models for disparate impact across demographic groups\n- Implement ongoing monitoring to detect fairness drift over time\n- Maintain audit trails enabling reconstruction of AIDA-driven decisions\n- Provide recourse mechanisms for customers who believe they were treated unfairly\n- Conduct regular fairness audits with findings reported to senior management\n\nETHICS\nFIs must embed ethical considerations throughout the AIDA development and deployment lifecycle:\n- Establish ethics review processes for new AIDA use cases, particularly those with significant customer impact\n- Appoint ethics oversight function (may be integrated with existing risk governance)\n- Maintain human judgment in high-stakes decisions affecting customer welfare\n- Avoid deploying AIDA in ways that exploit customer vulnerabilities or information asymmetries\n- Consider societal implications beyond individual customer impacts\n\nACCOUNTABILITY\nClear accountability structures must govern AIDA use:\n- Designate senior accountable officer for each material AIDA use case\n- Document roles and responsibilities for data scientists, model risk managers, business owners, and compliance functions\n- Establish model governance frameworks covering development, validation, approval, deployment, monitoring, and decommissioning\n- Ensure model risk management frameworks address AIDA-specific risks including model drift, adversarial attacks, and explainability limitations\n- Conduct independent model validation before deployment for high-impact use cases\n- Report material AIDA incidents and model failures to Board and senior management\n\nTRANSPARENCY\nFIs must be transparent about AIDA use with customers and regulators:\n- Disclose to customers when significant decisions are made using AIDA\n- Provide explanations of AIDA-driven decisions in plain language upon customer request\n- Maintain documentation enabling regulatory examination of AIDA systems\n- Publish meaningful public disclosure about the FI's overall AI governance approach\n\nVERITAS INITIATIVE\nMAS launched the Veritas Consortium in 2019 to develop practical fairness assessment methodologies for AIDA use in financial services. Veritas Phase 2 produced open-source assessment tools covering three use cases:\n\n1. Credit Risk Scoring: Methodologies for assessing group fairness, counterfactual fairness, and individual fairness in credit decisions. Tools measure disparate impact ratio, equalized odds, and calibration across demographic groups.\n\n2. Customer Marketing: Fairness metrics for targeted marketing including equal opportunity in product offering and avoiding exploitation of vulnerable populations.\n\n3. Customer Fraud Detection: Balancing fraud detection accuracy with false positive rates across demographic groups to avoid disproportionate burden on any group.\n\nThe Veritas toolkit is publicly available on GitHub and FIs are encouraged to use it as a starting point for their own fairness assessment programs.\n\nMAS MODEL RISK MANAGEMENT GUIDELINES\nMAS published Model Risk Management (MRM) Guidelines in June 2023 providing detailed expectations for banks' model risk management frameworks, with specific guidance on AI/ML models. Key requirements:\n- Maintain model inventory covering all models including AI/ML\n- Conduct tiered model validation proportionate to model materiality and complexity\n- Address AI-specific risks: overfitting, data leakage, distributional shift, adversarial robustness\n- Ensure model explainability appropriate to the use case; document explainability approach in model documentation\n- Monitor models post-deployment with pre-defined performance thresholds triggering review\n- Maintain model governance documentation accessible to MAS examiners\n\nGENERATIVE AI GUIDANCE\nMAS issued guidance in 2024 on responsible use of generative AI in financial services, highlighting:\n- Hallucination risks and the need for human review of AI-generated content used in customer communications or regulatory filings\n- Third-party model risks when using foundation models from external providers\n- Intellectual property and confidentiality considerations in using public LLM services\n- Vendor due diligence requirements for AI service providers including assessment of training data practices, model governance, and incident response capabilities\n\nSINGAPORE MODEL AI GOVERNANCE FRAMEWORK (PERSONAL DATA PROTECTION COMMISSION)\nComplementing MAS guidance, the PDPC's Model AI Governance Framework (2nd edition, 2020) applies across sectors. It is structured around two guiding principles:\n1. AI decisions should be explainable, transparent, and fair to consumers\n2. AI systems should be human-centric, with humans remaining responsible for outcomes\n\nThe Framework's four areas: (1) Internal Governance Structures and Measures, (2) Determining AI Decision-Making Model, (3) Operations Management, (4) Stakeholder Interaction and Communication.\n\nPRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION FOR FIs IN SINGAPORE\n- Map AIDA use cases to FEAT principles and assess compliance gaps\n- Implement or enhance model governance framework to address AI/ML lifecycle\n- Deploy Veritas fairness assessment tools for customer-facing credit and marketing models\n- Establish customer explainability capability for AIDA-driven decisions\n- Train model developers and validators on FEAT requirements and MRM Guidelines\n- Brief Board and senior management on AIDA governance program\n- Prepare for MAS thematic examination of AI governance practices (conducted periodically)",
    "price_usdc": 0,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
