    "memory_id": "ghm_026",
    "title": "California CCPA Agent Data Handling Rules",
    "category": "ai_compliance",
    "content": "`The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) as amended by the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA) creates significant compliance obligations for businesses deploying AI agents that collect, process, or share personal information of California residents. This guide covers the rules most relevant to agentic AI systems.\n\nSCOPE AND APPLICABILITY\nThe CCPA/CPRA applies to for-profit businesses that: (1) have gross annual revenues exceeding $25 million; (2) annually buy, sell, or share personal information of 100,000 or more consumers or households; or (3) derive 50% or more of annual revenue from selling or sharing personal information. For AI agents, even small businesses may meet threshold (2) if the agent processes large volumes of consumer data.\n\nCATEGORIES OF PERSONAL INFORMATION RELEVANT TO AGENTS\nThe CCPA broadly defines personal information to include any information that identifies, relates to, describes, is capable of being associated with, or could reasonably be linked with a particular consumer or household. For AI agents this includes:\n- Identifiers: names, email addresses, IP addresses, device identifiers, cookies\n- Commercial information: purchase history, browsing history, preferences\n- Biometric information: if agent uses voice recognition, facial features, or other biometric data\n- Internet or electronic network activity: interactions with the agent, search history within the agent\n- Geolocation data: if agent uses location services\n- Inferences drawn from personal information: profiles about consumer preferences, behavior, or characteristics created by the agent\n\nThe CPRA created a new category of \"sensitive personal information\" with additional protections including: Social Security numbers, financial account details, precise geolocation, racial/ethnic origin, religious beliefs, contents of personal communications, health information, and sexual orientation.\n\nCONSUMER RIGHTS UNDER CCPA/CPRA FOR AGENT INTERACTIONS\n\nRight to Know (Section 1798.100): Consumers can request disclosure of the categories and specific pieces of personal information the business has collected about them, the sources from which it was collected, the purposes for collection, and the categories of third parties with whom it is shared. Agents must maintain records adequate to respond to these requests.\n\nRight to Delete (Section 1798.105): Consumers can request deletion of personal information the business has collected about them. This extends to agent memory stores, conversation logs, derived profiles, and any copies shared with service providers. Businesses must direct service providers to delete the information as well. Several exceptions apply including where information is necessary to complete a transaction or detect security incidents.\n\nRight to Correct (Section 1798.106): Added by CPRA, consumers can request correction of inaccurate personal information. Agent systems containing consumer profiles or persistent memories must have correction capability.\n\nRight to Opt-Out of Sale or Sharing (Section 1798.120): Consumers can direct the business not to sell or share their personal information. \"Sharing\" under CPRA includes cross-context behavioral advertising. Agents that pass consumer interaction data to advertising networks or analytics platforms that use it for cross-context behavioral advertising must honor opt-out signals including Global Privacy Control.\n\nRight to Limit Use of Sensitive Personal Information (Section 1798.121): Consumers can limit the use of sensitive personal information to what is necessary to perform requested services. Agents using sensitive categories for secondary purposes must honor limitation requests.\n\nRight of No Retaliation: Businesses cannot discriminate against consumers for exercising CCPA rights by denying goods/services, charging different prices, or providing different service quality.\n\nAUTOMATED DECISION-MAKING TECHNOLOGY REGULATIONS\nThe California Privacy Protection Agency (CPPA) has issued draft regulations on automated decision-making technology (ADMT) that will significantly affect AI agents. Key provisions in the draft regulations:\n- Pre-use notice: Businesses must provide notice before using ADMT for significant decisions affecting consumers (employment, housing, credit, healthcare, education, or access to essential services)\n- Right to opt-out: Consumers will have the right to opt-out of ADMT use for significant decisions and behavioral advertising\n- Right to access: Consumers can request information about how ADMT affecting them functions\n- Risk assessment requirement: Businesses using ADMT must conduct and document risk assessments evaluating potential harms to consumers\n\nSERVICE PROVIDER AND CONTRACTOR REQUIREMENTS\nWhen AI agents are built using third-party components or APIs, contractual requirements apply:\n- Service providers receiving personal information from the business must use it only for specified business purposes, not for their own commercial purposes, and must provide at least equivalent consumer rights\n- Contracts must prohibit service providers from selling or sharing personal information\n- Businesses must conduct due diligence on service providers' privacy practices\n- Foundation model API providers used by agents must be classified as service providers with appropriate contractual protections\n\nPRIVACY POLICY DISCLOSURE REQUIREMENTS\nBusiness privacy policies must disclose all categories of personal information collected by AI agents, the purposes for which each category is collected or used, how long each category is retained, whether personal information is sold or shared, categories of third parties with whom it is shared, and the consumer rights available and how to exercise them. For agents, this requires careful documentation of all data flows including interaction data, memory contents, and analytics.\n\nDATA MINIMIZATION UNDER CPRA\nCPRA added explicit data minimization requirements: collection, use, retention, and sharing of personal information must be reasonably necessary and proportionate to the purposes for which it is collected. For AI agents, this requires:\n- Justification for all personal information collected during agent interactions\n- Retention schedules limiting how long agent conversation logs and memory data are kept\n- Purpose documentation ensuring agent analytics do not repurpose data incompatibly\n\nSECURITY REQUIREMENTS\nBusinesses must implement reasonable security measures commensurate with the sensitivity of the personal information. For AI agents handling financial, health, or other sensitive information, enhanced security controls are required. The CPPA's security regulations define reasonable security with reference to the CIS Controls and other recognized frameworks.\n\nENFORCEMENT AND PENALTIES\nThe CPPA enforces CCPA/CPRA with civil penalties up to $2,500 per unintentional violation and $7,500 per intentional violation or violation involving a minor's personal information. Private right of action exists for data breaches involving certain categories of personal information at $100-$750 per consumer per incident. The CPPA conducts investigations and audits and can impose administrative fines.",
