    "memory_id": "ghm_056",
    "title": "USDC Integration Guide for Agents",
    "category": "financial_defi",
    "content": "`USDC (USD Coin) is the dominant stablecoin for agent-to-agent payments due to its regulatory clarity, widespread exchange support, and native deployment on multiple chains. This guide covers end-to-end integration for autonomous agents.\n\n**Contract Addresses**\n\nUSDC is an ERC-20 token. Key addresses (always verify from official Circle documentation before deploying):\n- Ethereum Mainnet: 0xA0b86991c6218b36c1d19D4a2e9Eb0cE3606eB48\n- Base Mainnet: 0x833589fCD6eDb6E08f4c7C32D4f71b54bdA02913\n- Arbitrum One: 0xaf88d065e77c8cC2239327C5EDb3A432268e5831\n- Solana: EPjFWdd5AufqSSqeM2qN1xzybapC8G4wEGGkZwyTDt1v\n\n**ABI Essentials**\n\nFor agent wallets, you need these functions from the ERC-20 interface:\n\\`\\`\\`\nbalanceOf(address) → uint256\ntransfer(address to, uint256 amount) → bool\napprove(address spender, uint256 amount) → bool\ntransferFrom(address from, address to, uint256 amount) → bool\nallowance(address owner, address spender) → uint256\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nUSDC uses 6 decimal places, not 18. A payment of $1.00 is represented as \\`1_000_000\\` (1e6). Always use BigInt arithmetic in JavaScript/TypeScript to avoid floating-point errors:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nconst ONE_DOLLAR = 1_000_000n; // 1 USDC in base units\nconst amount = BigInt(Math.round(priceUSD * 1e6));\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Approval Patterns**\n\nBefore a contract can spend USDC on your agent's behalf, it must be approved. Two patterns are common:\n\n1. *Exact approval*: Approve exactly the amount needed. Safer, but requires a separate transaction per payment, increasing gas costs.\n2. *Max approval*: \\`approve(spender, type(uint256).max)\\` once, then spend freely. Common in production but increases attack surface if the spender contract is compromised.\n\nFor agent treasuries handling many small payments, a middle ground is to approve a daily budget (e.g., 100 USDC) and top it up via a scheduled task.\n\n**Permit (EIP-2612)**\n\nNative USDC (deployed by Circle after 2023) supports EIP-2612 permit signatures. This allows agents to sign an off-chain authorization that can be submitted alongside a transaction, eliminating the separate approve transaction:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nconst { v, r, s } = await signPermit({\n  owner: agentAddress,\n  spender: contractAddress,\n  value: amount,\n  nonce: await usdc.nonces(agentAddress),\n  deadline: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000) + 3600,\n});\nawait contract.depositWithPermit(amount, deadline, v, r, s);\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nThis saves one transaction (~21,000 gas on mainnet) and improves UX for single-step flows.\n\n**Cross-Chain USDC: CCTP**\n\nCircle's Cross-Chain Transfer Protocol (CCTP) enables native USDC burns on the source chain and mints on the destination chain. This is preferable to bridge-wrapped USDC because it avoids liquidity fragmentation and bridge risk.\n\nFlow for agent payments across chains:\n1. Call \\`depositForBurn\\` on the source chain TokenMessenger contract.\n2. Poll Circle's attestation API for the signed message (typically 13–20 seconds on fast finality chains).\n3. Call \\`receiveMessage\\` on the destination chain MessageTransmitter with the attestation.\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nconst attestation = await pollAttestation(messageHash, { maxWait: 60_000 });\nawait destinationMessenger.receiveMessage(message, attestation);\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nFor agent automation, cache the CCTP contract ABIs and run the attestation poller as a background coroutine to avoid blocking payment flows.\n\n**Balance Monitoring**\n\nAgents should monitor USDC balances proactively rather than reactively failing on insufficient funds:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nasync function checkTreasury(minBalance = 10_000_000n) { // $10 minimum\n  const balance = await usdc.balanceOf(agentWallet);\n  if (balance < minBalance) {\n    await emit('treasury.low', { balance, threshold: minBalance });\n  }\n  return balance;\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Security Considerations**\n\n- Never store private keys in environment variables in production; use KMS (AWS, GCP, HashiCorp Vault) or hardware wallets.\n- Validate all incoming payment amounts before processing; reject zero-value transfers.\n- For high-value operations, implement a time-lock: queue the transaction, wait 30–60 minutes, then execute unless cancelled.\n- Log all transfer events with transaction hashes and amounts to your audit trail for reconciliation.\n- USDC contracts can be paused by Circle in emergency situations; implement fallback payment paths using alternative stablecoins (USDT, DAI) if availability is mission-critical.",
