    "memory_id": "ghm_058",
    "title": "Agent Treasury Management Best Practices",
    "category": "financial_defi",
    "content": "`An agent treasury is the on-chain wallet or smart contract that holds funds an agent uses to pay for services, stake in protocols, and receive revenue. Unlike human treasuries, agent treasuries must be managed autonomously, meaning all policies must be encoded as rules the agent can execute without human approval.\n\n**Treasury Architecture Patterns**\n\n*Single EOA (simplest)*: One externally-owned account holds all funds. Easy to implement but offers no spending controls, recovery mechanisms, or multi-sig protection. Only appropriate for development or low-value agents (under $100 total exposure).\n\n*Multi-sig Smart Wallet*: A contract like Safe (formerly Gnosis Safe) requires M-of-N signatures before executing transactions. For agent treasuries, configure 1-of-2 (agent key + operator key) for routine operations, with a 2-of-3 threshold for withdrawals above a configured limit. This prevents a compromised agent key from draining the entire treasury.\n\n*Modular Vault with Spending Policies*: The most robust pattern. A vault contract enforces rules:\n- Maximum spend per transaction\n- Maximum spend per time window (e.g., $500/day)\n- Allowlist of approved recipient addresses\n- Token allowlist (USDC only, no arbitrary ERC-20)\n- Emergency pause by operator\n\n\\`\\`\\`solidity\nmapping(address => bool) public approvedRecipients;\nuint256 public dailyLimit;\nuint256 public dailySpent;\nuint256 public dayStart;\n\nfunction spend(address to, uint256 amount) external onlyAgent {\n    if (block.timestamp >= dayStart + 1 days) {\n        dailySpent = 0;\n        dayStart = block.timestamp;\n    }\n    require(approvedRecipients[to], \"Recipient not approved\");\n    require(dailySpent + amount <= dailyLimit, \"Daily limit exceeded\");\n    dailySpent += amount;\n    usdc.transfer(to, amount);\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Liquidity Tiers**\n\nStructure the treasury across three liquidity tiers:\n\n1. *Hot wallet* (10–20% of assets): Immediately accessible. Covers expected operational expenses for the next 24–48 hours. Held in USDC in the agent's signing wallet. Never put yield-bearing positions here — the cost of position exits in urgent situations is too high.\n\n2. *Warm reserve* (50–60% of assets): Available within minutes. Invested in low-risk yield sources (Aave USDC supply, Compound, or similar). Automated withdrawal logic triggered when hot wallet drops below threshold.\n\n3. *Cold reserve* (20–40% of assets): Long-term storage. May be in multi-sig, time-locked contracts, or higher-yield but less liquid positions. Requires manual or multi-sig authorization to access. Protects against agent key compromise draining all funds.\n\n**Automated Rebalancing**\n\nImplement a rebalancing coroutine that runs on a schedule (every 15–60 minutes):\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nasync function rebalanceTreasury() {\n  const hot = await usdc.balanceOf(hotWallet);\n  const target = DAILY_BUDGET * 2n; // 2 days of expected spend\n  \n  if (hot < target * 8n / 10n) { // Below 80% of target\n    const deficit = target - hot;\n    await warmReserve.withdraw(deficit); // Pull from Aave\n  } else if (hot > target * 15n / 10n) { // Above 150% of target\n    const excess = hot - target;\n    await warmReserve.deposit(excess); // Push to Aave\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Revenue Collection**\n\nAgents receiving payment for services should route revenue to a separate collection address, not the operating wallet. This separation makes accounting cleaner and prevents incoming payments from triggering false-positive alerts on spending monitors.\n\nSet up a sweep job that moves accumulated revenue from the collection address to the treasury warm reserve once daily or when it exceeds a threshold (e.g., $50).\n\n**Treasury Health Metrics**\n\nMonitor these continuously:\n- *Runway*: Current hot + warm balance ÷ average daily spend. Alert if under 7 days.\n- *Revenue vs. Cost ratio*: If costs exceed revenue for 3 consecutive days, pause non-essential operations.\n- *Yield efficiency*: Actual APY earned on warm reserve vs. benchmark (e.g., Aave current rate). Alert if more than 20% below benchmark, indicating a position issue.\n- *Slippage exposure*: If any DeFi position has unrealized loss > 2%, flag for review.\n\n**Gas Reserve Management**\n\nOn EVM chains, the agent needs native token (ETH on Base/Ethereum, MATIC on Polygon) for gas in addition to USDC. Maintain a separate gas reserve of 0.01–0.05 ETH on each chain where the agent operates.\n\nImplement automatic gas top-up via a bridge when the gas reserve drops below 0.005 ETH:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nasync function ensureGasReserve() {\n  const ethBalance = await provider.getBalance(agentWallet);\n  if (ethBalance < parseEther('0.005')) {\n    // Use a DEX or bridge to swap $5 of USDC for ETH\n    await swapUsdcForEth(5_000_000n); // $5 USDC\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Security and Recovery**\n\n- Store the recovery key (operator multi-sig) in a hardware wallet held by a human operator — never in software that the agent can access.\n- Implement a dead man's switch: if the agent fails to call a heartbeat function for 72 hours, the vault pauses all outgoing transactions until a human intervenes.\n- Maintain a complete audit log of every treasury transaction with amount, recipient, purpose, and timestamp. Store this in an append-only data store separate from the agent's operational database.\n- Test treasury recovery procedures quarterly: simulate the agent key being compromised and verify that operator recovery works as expected.",
    "price_usdc": 1.5,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
    "tags": [
      "treasury",
      "vault",
      "multi-sig",
      "liquidity",
      "rebalancing",
      "safe",
      "spending-limits",
      "security"
    ]
