    "memory_id": "ghm_059",
    "title": "Automated Market Making for Agent Services",
    "category": "financial_defi",
    "content": "`Automated Market Makers (AMMs) are a pricing mechanism where an algorithm sets prices based on the ratio of assets in a liquidity pool rather than relying on an order book. For agent service economies, AMM principles can be applied to dynamically price compute, API calls, and data access based on supply and demand.\n\n**Traditional AMM Mechanics**\n\nThe canonical AMM formula is the constant product invariant: \\`x * y = k\\`, where x and y are the quantities of two tokens in a pool and k is a constant. When a user buys token Y with token X, they add dx to the pool and receive dy from it, such that \\`(x + dx)(y - dy) = k\\`.\n\nUniswap V2 implements this directly. Uniswap V3 introduced *concentrated liquidity*, where liquidity providers specify a price range rather than distributing liquidity across all possible prices. This dramatically improves capital efficiency.\n\n**Applying AMM Pricing to Agent Services**\n\nAn agent marketplace can use AMM mechanics to price services dynamically without a central price-setting authority:\n\n1. *Service Capacity Pool*: Treat available compute units as one \"token\" and USDC as the other. When demand is high (capacity pool draining), prices rise automatically. When demand is low (capacity pool full), prices fall.\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nclass ServiceAMM {\n  constructor(capacityUnits, usdcReserve) {\n    this.capacity = BigInt(capacityUnits);\n    this.usdc = BigInt(usdcReserve);\n    this.k = this.capacity * this.usdc;\n  }\n  \n  priceForUnits(units) {\n    const newCapacity = this.capacity - BigInt(units);\n    if (newCapacity <= 0n) throw new Error('Insufficient capacity');\n    const newUsdc = this.k / newCapacity;\n    return newUsdc - this.usdc; // Cost in USDC base units\n  }\n  \n  executePayment(units, maxCost) {\n    const cost = this.priceForUnits(units);\n    if (cost > maxCost) throw new Error('Slippage exceeded');\n    this.capacity -= BigInt(units);\n    this.usdc += cost;\n    return cost;\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n2. *Slippage Protection*: Always pass a \\`maxCost\\` parameter equivalent to a human setting a slippage tolerance. For agent-to-agent payments, 0.5% slippage is reasonable; for time-sensitive operations, you may tolerate up to 2%.\n\n**Liquidity Provisioning for Agent Networks**\n\nIn a multi-agent network, agents with excess capacity can provide liquidity to the service pool, earning fees from agents consuming capacity. This creates an incentive for agents to smooth demand peaks by pre-provisioning capacity.\n\nFee structures for agent service AMMs:\n- *Flat fee*: e.g., 0.3% of transaction value goes to liquidity providers (Uniswap V2 default)\n- *Dynamic fee*: Higher fees during high-volatility periods (when many agents compete for scarce capacity), lower fees during stable periods\n- *Provider tiering*: Agents providing locked liquidity for 30+ days earn higher fee share than just-in-time providers\n\n**Concentrated Liquidity for Known Price Ranges**\n\nIf your agent service has a known price range (e.g., compute always between $0.001–$0.01 per unit), using Uniswap V3-style concentrated liquidity provides much better capital efficiency:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\n// Provide liquidity only between price ticks 100 (min $0.001) and 1000 (max $0.01)\nawait pool.mint({\n  tickLower: priceToTick(0.001),\n  tickUpper: priceToTick(0.01),\n  amount: liquidityAmount,\n  recipient: agentAddress,\n});\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nCapital efficiency gain vs. full-range LP: ~10–50× for a ±10% price range.\n\n**Price Impact and Large Orders**\n\nFor large service orders (e.g., an agent requesting 1000 units when average order is 10), the AMM price impact can be significant. Implement order splitting:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nasync function splitLargeOrder(units, maxPriceImpact = 0.02) {\n  const basePrice = amm.priceForUnits(1);\n  const chunkSize = estimateChunkSize(units, maxPriceImpact, amm);\n  const chunks = Math.ceil(units / chunkSize);\n  \n  let totalCost = 0n;\n  for (let i = 0; i < chunks; i++) {\n    const size = Math.min(chunkSize, units - i * chunkSize);\n    totalCost += await amm.executePayment(size, maxPrice);\n    // Optional: wait for state refresh between chunks\n  }\n  return totalCost;\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**TWAP Oracles for Agent Pricing Decisions**\n\nAMMs also serve as on-chain price oracles via Time-Weighted Average Price (TWAP). For agents that need a tamper-resistant price feed (e.g., for collateral valuation or settlement):\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\n// Uniswap V3 TWAP: average price over last 30 minutes\nconst [tick] = await pool.observe([1800, 0]); // 30min ago vs now\nconst twapPrice = tickToPrice(tick);\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nTWAP is manipulation-resistant because an attacker would need to maintain an off-market price for the entire window, which is prohibitively expensive.\n\n**Rebalancing Agent Service Pools**\n\nAMM liquidity pools drift toward one asset when price moves significantly. For service AMMs, implement a rebalancing bot that:\n1. Monitors the capacity-to-USDC ratio in the pool.\n2. When the pool is >70% USDC (demand is low, capacity unsold), the bot buys back capacity at a discount.\n3. When the pool is >70% capacity (demand is high, USDC depleted), the bot adds USDC reserves to smooth prices.\n\nThis prevents the AMM from reaching extreme states where prices become too high (during demand spikes) or too low (during demand droughts) to function practically.",
    "price_usdc": 2,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
