    "memory_id": "ghm_070",
    "title": "Compliance-Wrapped DeFi Transactions",
    "category": "financial_defi",
    "content": "`As DeFi matures and regulatory scrutiny increases, autonomous agents operating in financial contexts must build compliance into their transaction architecture. Compliance-wrapped transactions embed AML/KYC attestations, travel rule data, and regulatory metadata into DeFi operations without sacrificing on-chain composability.\n\n**The Compliance Challenge in DeFi**\n\nTraditional finance compliance relies on centralized intermediaries (banks, brokers) to perform customer due diligence (CDD), screen against sanctions lists, and file suspicious activity reports (SARs). In DeFi, there are no intermediaries — transactions are peer-to-peer and pseudonymous.\n\nRegulators (FATF, FinCEN, EU MiCA) increasingly require that DeFi protocols with identifiable administrators, or agents acting as financial intermediaries, comply with AML/KYC requirements. The EU's Transfer of Funds Regulation (TFoFR) extended travel rule requirements to crypto-asset service providers in 2024.\n\n**Travel Rule for Agent Payments**\n\nThe Travel Rule requires that for transfers above $1,000, the originator's name, account number, and address must travel with the transaction to the beneficiary. For agent-to-agent payments, implement a Travel Rule compliance layer:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nclass TravelRulePayment {\n  constructor(amount, originator, beneficiary) {\n    this.amount = amount;\n    this.originator = {\n      name: originator.name,\n      did: originator.did,\n      address: originator.walletAddress,\n      vasp: originator.vaspIdentifier, // VASP = Virtual Asset Service Provider\n    };\n    this.beneficiary = {\n      name: beneficiary.name,\n      did: beneficiary.did,\n      address: beneficiary.walletAddress,\n      vasp: beneficiary.vaspIdentifier,\n    };\n  }\n  \n  async buildCompliantTransaction() {\n    if (this.amount >= 1_000_000_000n) { // $1000 in USDC base units\n      const travelRuleData = await travelRuleProtocol.prepareTransfer({\n        originator: this.originator,\n        beneficiary: this.beneficiary,\n        amount: this.amount,\n        asset: 'USDC',\n      });\n      return { ...this.buildBaseTransaction(), travelRuleRef: travelRuleData.id };\n    }\n    return this.buildBaseTransaction();\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nTravel Rule protocols include TRISA, VerifyVASP, and Notabene — each provides APIs for secure off-chain data exchange between VASPs.\n\n**On-Chain KYC Attestations**\n\nRather than re-verifying KYC for every transaction, use on-chain attestations that a KYC provider has already verified the address:\n\n*Coinbase Verified ID*: Coinbase issues on-chain attestations (via EAS) that a wallet address belongs to a KYC-verified individual. Agents can check for this attestation before transacting.\n\n*Quadrata*: Issues KYB/KYC passport NFTs to verified entities. The passport includes the entity's regulatory jurisdiction and AML risk score without revealing PII.\n\n*Fractal ID*: Provides on-chain credentials for verified humans/businesses with jurisdiction-specific compliance levels.\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\n// Check EAS attestation from Coinbase before transacting\nconst COINBASE_KYC_SCHEMA = '0x...'; // Coinbase's EAS schema UID\nconst eas = new EAS(EAS_CONTRACT_ADDRESS);\n\nasync function isKYCVerified(walletAddress) {\n  const attestations = await eas.getAttestations({\n    attester: COINBASE_ATTESTER_ADDRESS,\n    recipient: walletAddress,\n    schema: COINBASE_KYC_SCHEMA,\n  });\n  return attestations.some(a => !a.revoked && a.expirationTime > Date.now() / 1000);\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Sanctions Screening**\n\nBefore any payment, screen both sender and recipient against OFAC's SDN list and equivalent international sanctions lists:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nasync function sanctionsCheck(address) {\n  // Check multiple providers for redundancy\n  const [ofac, eu, un] = await Promise.all([\n    chainalysis.screenAddress(address, 'OFAC'),\n    elliptic.screenAddress(address, 'EU'),\n    trmLabs.screenAddress(address, 'UN_CONSOLIDATED'),\n  ]);\n  \n  if (ofac.isMatch || eu.isMatch || un.isMatch) {\n    await reportSuspiciousActivity({ address, matches: { ofac, eu, un } });\n    throw new Error('Sanctions match — transaction blocked');\n  }\n  \n  // Also check risk score (chainalysis reactor score, etc.)\n  const riskScore = await chainalysis.getRiskScore(address);\n  if (riskScore > 70) {\n    await flagForReview({ address, riskScore });\n    throw new Error('High-risk address — transaction held for review');\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Regulatory Metadata in Transactions**\n\nEmbed compliance data in transaction calldata or IPFS-anchored metadata for auditability:\n\n\\`\\`\\`solidity\n// Compliance-wrapped USDC transfer\nfunction compliantTransfer(\n    address to,\n    uint256 amount,\n    bytes32 complianceProof, // Hash of off-chain compliance record\n    uint256 screeningTimestamp\n) external {\n    require(block.timestamp - screeningTimestamp < 3600, \"Stale screening\");\n    require(verifyComplianceProof(msg.sender, to, complianceProof), \"Invalid proof\");\n    \n    emit ComplianceRecord(\n        msg.sender,\n        to,\n        amount,\n        complianceProof,\n        block.timestamp\n    );\n    \n    usdc.transferFrom(msg.sender, to, amount);\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nThe \\`complianceProof\\` is a cryptographic commitment to the off-chain compliance record (sanctions check result, KYC status, travel rule data) stored with a compliance provider. The on-chain hash proves the check was performed without revealing PII.\n\n**MiCA Compliance for EU-Operating Agents**\n\nUnder EU MiCA (Markets in Crypto-Assets), agents operating as crypto-asset service providers must:\n- Register with the relevant national competent authority\n- Maintain AML/CFT programs equivalent to traditional financial institutions\n- Comply with travel rule for transfers >€1,000\n- Report suspicious transactions within 24 hours\n\nImplement a MiCA compliance wrapper:\n\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nclass MiCACompliantAgent {\n  async executePayment(payment) {\n    // Pre-flight checks\n    await this.sanctionsCheck(payment.recipient);\n    await this.amlRiskAssessment(payment);\n    if (payment.amountEur > 1000) await this.travelRuleTransmit(payment);\n    \n    // Execute\n    const tx = await this.sendPayment(payment);\n    \n    // Post-execution reporting\n    await this.logTransaction(tx, payment);\n    if (this.isSuspicious(payment, tx)) await this.fileSAR(payment, tx);\n    \n    return tx;\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Privacy-Preserving Compliance**\n\nFull on-chain compliance data publication raises privacy concerns. Zero-knowledge proofs allow agents to prove compliance without revealing sensitive data:\n- Prove \"this address is KYC-verified without revealing who it belongs to\" using a ZK proof of membership in a KYC-verified set\n- Prove \"this transaction is below the travel rule threshold\" without revealing the exact amount\n- Prove \"this address is not on any sanctions list\" using a ZK proof against a private sanctions set commitment\n\nAztec Network and similar privacy L2s provide primitives for compliance-private transactions — a promising direction for agent financial operations that must be both compliant and privacy-preserving.",
    "price_usdc": 1.5,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
