    "title": "Healthcare Data Processing Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Healthcare Data Processing Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nA Healthcare Data Processing Agent automates the ingestion, normalization, de-identification, validation, and routing of clinical and administrative healthcare data. It operates within the complex regulatory environment of HIPAA, HL7 FHIR standards, and state health information laws while delivering data to downstream consumers including analytics platforms, care coordination systems, and payer interfaces. This blueprint is a comprehensive technical and compliance guide for building this agent.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Multi-Format Data Ingestion\nHealthcare data arrives in a bewildering variety of formats and transport mechanisms. The agent must handle:\n- **HL7 v2.x messages** (ADT, ORM, ORU, MDM, SIU) via MLLP listener on configurable TCP ports\n- **HL7 FHIR R4 resources** via RESTful API (FHIR server integration, both as client and as a FHIR facade)\n- **CDA/CCDA documents** (Continuity of Care Documents) via XDS.b or FHIR DocumentReference\n- **X12 EDI transactions** (837 claims, 835 remittances, 270/271 eligibility, 278 authorization) via AS2 or SFTP\n- **DICOM** metadata extraction for radiology orders and imaging results\n- **CSV/Excel extracts** from legacy systems that cannot produce standards-compliant output\n\nImplement an inbound routing layer that detects message format, validates the envelope structure, and routes to the appropriate parser. All inbound messages are persisted to an immutable audit store before any transformation begins — this ensures replay capability for reprocessing when transformation logic is updated.\n\n### 2. Terminology Normalization and Clinical Coding\nClinical data uses dozens of overlapping coding systems. The agent normalizes to canonical representations:\n- **Diagnosis codes**: ICD-10-CM (validate against current fiscal year code set; flag retired or invalid codes)\n- **Procedure codes**: CPT-4, HCPCS Level II, ICD-10-PCS for inpatient procedures\n- **Medications**: normalize to RxNorm CUI; map NDC codes to RxNorm; flag medications with active FDA safety alerts\n- **Lab results**: LOINC codes for test identification; SNOMED CT for result interpretation\n- **Vital signs**: normalize units (Fahrenheit to Celsius, lbs to kg) and flag out-of-range values per NCHS reference ranges\n\nUse the UMLS Metathesaurus API (NLM) for cross-mapping between terminologies. For unmapped codes, trigger a terminology governance workflow that queues the unknown code for a clinical informaticist review rather than silently dropping or misclassifying the data.\n\n### 3. HIPAA De-identification and Privacy Controls\nThe agent must support both Safe Harbor and Expert Determination de-identification methods:\n\n**Safe Harbor De-identification (per 45 CFR §164.514(b)):**\n- Remove all 18 PHI identifiers: names, geographic subdivisions smaller than state, dates (except year) for individuals over 89, phone/fax numbers, email addresses, SSNs, MRNs, health plan beneficiary numbers, account numbers, certificate/license numbers, VINs, device identifiers, URLs, IPs, biometric identifiers, full-face photos, and any other unique identifying numbers or codes\n- Generalize ZIP codes to first 3 digits; suppress if the 3-digit ZIP represents fewer than 20,000 people (per NCHS mapping)\n- Apply date shifting with a consistent per-patient offset to preserve temporal relationships while obscuring actual dates\n\n**Expert Determination support:**\n- Integrate with a statistical de-identification service to assess re-identification risk scores\n- Flag datasets where quasi-identifier combinations (age + ZIP + diagnosis) create k-anonymity violations (k < 5)\n\nMaintain a separate key management service that stores linkage keys for re-identification when legally authorized (e.g., for public health reporting or legal proceedings).\n\n### 4. Data Quality Validation\nBefore routing data to downstream systems:\n- **Completeness checks**: required fields per message type (patient identifier, encounter date, sending facility)\n- **Consistency checks**: start date before end date; patient age consistent with date of birth; procedure codes consistent with patient sex\n- **Referential integrity**: patient identifier exists in MPI (Master Patient Index); ordering provider NPI validates against NPPES registry; facility NPI validates against CMS certification database\n- **Clinical plausibility**: lab values within physiologically possible ranges; medication doses within safe dosing ranges per published formularies (flag, do not block)\n- **Duplicate detection**: apply probabilistic matching (Fellegi-Sunter algorithm) to identify duplicate records across facilities\n\nAll validation failures are categorized by severity: Fatal (reject message, quarantine, notify sender), Error (route with error annotation, require human review before downstream delivery), Warning (route with annotation, log for trend monitoring).\n\n### 5. Master Patient Index (MPI) Management\nAccurate patient identity management is foundational. The agent:\n- Evaluates each incoming patient record against the enterprise MPI using deterministic matching (exact match on SSN, MRN combinations) followed by probabilistic matching (weighted score across name phonetic codes, DOB, address, insurance ID)\n- Assigns or confirms an Enterprise Master Patient Identifier (EMPI) for every record\n- Flags potential duplicates with a confidence score and routes low-confidence matches to an identity resolution queue for manual adjudication\n- Applies overlay protection rules for patients who have requested identity protection (domestic violence, VIP, correctional)\n\n### 6. Downstream Routing and Delivery\nOnce a message is validated and normalized:\n- Route to subscribed downstream systems based on message type, facility, and patient consent profile\n- Apply consent directives (stored as FHIR Consent resources) to suppress routing of sensitive categories (substance abuse records under 42 CFR Part 2, HIV status, mental health, genetic information) when the receiving system lacks the appropriate data use agreement\n- Deliver via the consuming system's preferred transport: HL7 v2 MLLP, FHIR REST, SFTP file drops, or event streaming (Kafka topic per data category)\n- Track delivery acknowledgments and implement retry logic with exponential backoff for failed deliveries\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### Compliance and Security Architecture\n- All data at rest encrypted with AES-256; all data in transit via TLS 1.2+\n- FHIR server access controlled via SMART on FHIR authorization (OAuth 2.0 with patient and user launch contexts)\n- Comprehensive audit logging per HIPAA §164.312(b): every access, disclosure, and modification of PHI is logged with user identity, timestamp, action, and affected data elements\n- Business Associate Agreements (BAAs) required before any data sharing with downstream systems; BAA registry maintained with expiration tracking\n\n### Scalability Considerations\n- Design for horizontal scaling of the parsing and validation workers using a queue-based architecture (SQS, RabbitMQ, or Kafka)\n- Target throughput: 10,000 HL7 messages per minute per processing node for high-volume hospital integrations\n- Implement circuit breakers for downstream system integrations to prevent cascade failures when a consuming system is degraded\n\n## Key Performance Indicators\n- Message processing latency (target: P99 under 5 seconds for real-time ADT feeds)\n- Data quality pass rate (target: 99.5%+ for validated sources)\n- Duplicate patient rate in MPI (target: under 1%)\n- PHI de-identification validation error rate (target: 0%)\n- Downstream delivery success rate (target: 99.9%)",
