    "memory_id": "ghm_076",
    "title": "Insurance Claims Processing Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Insurance Claims Processing Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nAn Insurance Claims Processing Agent automates the end-to-end claims lifecycle — from First Notice of Loss (FNOL) through investigation, coverage determination, settlement calculation, and payment. This blueprint addresses the full complexity of multi-line insurance claims processing including fraud detection integration, regulatory compliance, and subrogation identification.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. First Notice of Loss (FNOL) Intake\nThe agent accepts FNOL submissions through multiple channels and creates a structured claim record:\n- **Web portal submissions**: parse structured form data into the claims management system\n- **Phone transcription**: process call center recordings using ASR (automatic speech recognition) + NLU to extract claim details; flag calls exhibiting suspicious patterns for human review\n- **Email and document parsing**: extract claimant information, loss date, loss description, and policy number from unstructured emails and attached photos or documents\n- **Partner API submissions**: receive structured FNOL data from auto dealers, body shops, hospitals, and restoration contractors via REST API\n\nUpon FNOL creation, the agent immediately:\n1. Validates the policy number and confirms the policy was in force on the loss date\n2. Confirms the reported loss type is a covered peril under the applicable policy form\n3. Assigns a claim number from the configured sequence\n4. Sets the claim's regulatory acknowledgment due date (most states require acknowledgment within 10-15 days) and queues the acknowledgment workflow\n5. Assigns the claim to an adjuster queue based on line of business, loss complexity, and geographic territory\n\n### 2. Coverage Analysis\nBefore any investigation resources are committed, the agent performs a structured coverage analysis:\n- Parse the policy declarations page and applicable endorsements to extract coverage limits, deductibles, exclusions, and conditions\n- Map the reported loss circumstances to the policy language using a coverage ontology that cross-references loss types against each coverage grant and exclusion\n- Flag coverage issues that require a reservation of rights (ROR) letter — e.g., potential late notice, potential exclusion applicability, potential fraud\n- Calculate applicable deductibles including inflation-indexed deductibles, percentage-of-insured-value wind/hail deductibles, and split deductibles\n\nFor complex commercial lines claims with multiple coverage towers (primary, umbrella, excess), map the coverage waterfall and identify which carriers must be notified and at what loss thresholds.\n\n### 3. Investigation and Documentation Management\nThe agent coordinates and tracks the investigation workflow:\n- **Field inspection assignment**: based on loss type and geography, assign an independent adjuster (IA) or staff adjuster; transmit assignment with all claim details and access credentials\n- **Document collection**: generate targeted document request lists based on loss type (auto: police report, photos, repair estimate; property: mortgage statement, prior loss history, contractor estimates; liability: incident report, witness statements, medical records)\n- **Vendor management**: dispatch approved vendors (restoration contractors, forensic accountants, independent medical examiners) and track assignment acceptance, status updates, and report delivery\n- **Timeline monitoring**: track all regulatory deadlines (written acknowledgment, coverage determination, payment after acceptance) and alert when deadlines are within 5 business days\n\nFor each piece of received documentation, the agent:\n- Extracts key data points using OCR + NLP (medical records: diagnosis codes, treatment dates, billing amounts; estimates: line items, parts, labor rates)\n- Validates document authenticity indicators (flagging possible alterations or inconsistencies)\n- Indexes the document to the claim record with full-text search capability\n\n### 4. Valuation and Reserve Setting\nThe agent maintains and updates claim reserves throughout the lifecycle:\n- **Property claims**: calculate replacement cost value (RCV) and actual cash value (ACV) using Xactimate integration; compare contractor estimates against database benchmarks; flag estimates exceeding benchmark by more than 15% for re-inspection\n- **Auto physical damage**: integrate with CCC ONE or Mitchell for total loss valuation; use VIN-decoded vehicle specs plus comparable sales data to calculate actual cash value; apply betterment reductions per policy\n- **Bodily injury**: apply a reserve model that considers medical specials, general damages (using jurisdiction-specific multiplier ranges), lost wages, and applicable policy limits; update reserve as medical treatment progresses\n- **Workers' compensation**: integrate with medical bill review systems; apply state fee schedule adjustments; calculate indemnity reserves based on average weekly wage and applicable disability classification\n\nDocument every reserve change with the underlying rationale to support audit and regulatory examination readiness.\n\n### 5. Fraud Detection Integration\nThe agent applies a multi-layer fraud detection approach:\n- **Rules-based red flags**: late reporting (>30 days), prior claims history pattern, loss shortly after policy inception or increase, suspicious loss circumstances\n- **Social network analysis**: identify shared addresses, phone numbers, or attorneys across multiple claims — rings often involve coordinated submissions\n- **External database checks**: ISO ClaimSearch for prior claims history across carriers; NICB (National Insurance Crime Bureau) for vehicle theft and fraud patterns; LexisNexis for public records cross-check\n- **ML scoring**: apply a gradient boosting model trained on confirmed fraud cases; route claims scoring above the threshold to the Special Investigations Unit (SIU)\n\nAll fraud referrals are documented with the specific basis for referral, maintaining the civil/criminal evidentiary standards that SIU investigations require.\n\n### 6. Settlement and Payment Processing\nWhen investigation is complete and coverage is confirmed:\n- Generate a settlement calculation worksheet with all components (property damage, ALE, medical, lost wages, pain and suffering, applicable offsets)\n- Apply subrogation offset if recovery from a negligent third party is expected\n- Apply coordination of benefits (COB) adjustments for health insurance or workers' comp offsets\n- Route settlements exceeding adjuster authority to the appropriate approval level\n- Generate settlement release and satisfaction documents via DocuSign with conditional logic based on claim type and jurisdiction requirements\n- Process payment via the configured disbursement method: check via lockbox, ACH transfer, or virtual card to contractor\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### State Machine Design\nModel each claim as a state machine with defined states (New, Under Investigation, Coverage Disputed, Approved, Settled, Subrogated, Closed) and allowed transitions. Each state has entry actions (triggered automations), exit conditions (required documentation or approvals), and SLA timers.\n\n### Regulatory Compliance Engine\nEncode state-specific claims handling regulations (Fair Claims Settlement Practices Acts) as a rules database:\n- Acknowledgment deadlines by state\n- Investigation completion deadlines\n- Proof of loss requirements\n- Payment deadlines after coverage acceptance\n\nThe engine evaluates each claim daily against applicable rules and generates compliance alerts when deadlines are approaching.\n\n### Integrations\n- Policy administration system (Guidewire PolicyCenter, Duck Creek, Applied Epic)\n- Claims management system (Guidewire ClaimCenter, Majesco, Snapsheet)\n- Medical bill review (Mitchell SmartAdvisor, Coventry MBR)\n- ISO ClaimSearch, NICB, LexisNexis RiskView\n- Payment: ACI Worldwide, CheckFree, virtual card providers",
