    "title": "Tax Preparation Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Tax Preparation Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nA Tax Preparation Agent automates the collection, organization, calculation, and filing of tax returns for individuals and small businesses. It integrates with financial institutions, accounting systems, and tax authority APIs to deliver accurate, audit-ready returns while managing multi-state and multi-entity complexity. This blueprint covers the full workflow from document ingestion through e-filing and post-filing compliance.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Document Collection and Data Ingestion\nTax preparation begins with gathering source documents. The agent manages a comprehensive document collection workflow:\n- **Financial institution integrations**: connect to banks, brokerages, and payroll processors via OAuth-secured API connections (Plaid, Yodlee, or direct FI APIs) to retrieve 1099 data, W-2 data, and transaction histories automatically\n- **OCR document processing**: accept scanned or photographed tax forms and extract data using a tax-form-specific OCR pipeline trained to recognize W-2s, 1099-INTs, 1099-DIVs, 1099-Bs, 1098s, K-1s, and state tax forms; validate extracted data against IRS form field specifications\n- **Prior year return import**: parse prior-year returns (PDF or XML) to pre-populate carryforward items: NOLs, capital loss carryforwards, passive activity loss carryforwards, AMT credits, charitable contribution carryforwards\n- **Accounting system pull**: for small business clients, connect to QuickBooks, Xero, or FreshBooks via API to pull the P&L, balance sheet, and detailed transaction ledger as the basis for Schedule C, E, or F preparation\n\nTrack document completeness against a dynamic checklist that adapts to the client's situation (e.g., if a 1099-B is detected, add Form 8949 preparation to the workflow; if rental income is detected, add Schedule E).\n\n### 2. Income Classification and Calculation\nThe agent classifies all income items into IRS categories:\n- Wages, salaries, tips (W-2 income) with proper Box 12 code handling for HSA contributions, 401(k) deferrals, and DCFSA\n- Interest and dividend income (qualified vs. non-qualified dividends determination for preferential rate treatment)\n- Capital gains and losses: apply the wash sale rule, identify long-term vs. short-term holding periods, calculate basis adjustments for corporate actions (stock splits, mergers, spinoffs) using a corporate actions database\n- Business income: apply QBI deduction eligibility rules (§199A), calculate self-employment tax, and identify applicable Section 179/bonus depreciation elections\n- Rental income: calculate depreciation schedules (27.5-year residential, 39-year commercial), apply passive activity loss rules, track at-risk limitations\n- Retirement distributions: determine taxable portion of IRA/pension distributions using annuity tables or prior basis tracking (Form 8606 history)\n\n### 3. Deduction Optimization\nThe agent systematically evaluates all deduction categories:\n- **Itemized vs. standard deduction comparison**: calculate itemized deductions (SALT capped at $10K, mortgage interest, charitable contributions, medical expenses above 7.5% AGI floor) and compare to the applicable standard deduction; recommend the higher option\n- **Above-the-line deductions**: identify and apply student loan interest, HSA contributions, self-employed health insurance, retirement contributions (Traditional IRA deductibility phase-out calculation for MAGI-based limits)\n- **Business deductions**: for Schedule C filers, validate deduction legitimacy against IRS guidance; flag mixed-use expenses (home office, vehicle) and apply the appropriate allocation methods with required substantiation documentation\n- **State tax optimization**: for multi-state filers, evaluate whether to claim a deduction for state taxes paid or a credit for taxes paid to other states — the optimal choice varies by state combination\n\n### 4. Tax Credit Identification and Calculation\nSystematically evaluate all applicable credits:\n- Child Tax Credit and Additional CTC: phase-out calculation based on filing status and MAGI\n- Earned Income Tax Credit: apply the complex eligibility rules including investment income limits; flag potential EITC audits when self-employment income is present\n- Child and Dependent Care Credit: calculate based on qualifying expenses, AGI-based percentage, and employer-provided dependent care FSA offsets\n- Education credits (American Opportunity, Lifetime Learning): verify eligibility, calculate qualified education expenses, apply phase-outs\n- Energy credits (residential clean energy, energy efficient home improvement): validate qualifying property per IRS Notice requirements\n- Retirement savings contributions credit (Saver's Credit): verify income eligibility and retirement contribution amounts\n- Premium Tax Credit: reconcile advance payments received against actual credit based on final year income; calculate repayment caps if income exceeded projections\n\n### 5. Multi-State Compliance\nFor taxpayers with income across multiple states:\n- Determine residency status for each state: full-year resident, part-year resident, or nonresident\n- Allocate income to each state using the applicable sourcing rules (domicile state, source state for W-2 and business income, pro-rata for investment income in most states)\n- Calculate and apply credits for taxes paid to other states to prevent double taxation\n- Track statutory residency rules for states with aggressive domicile enforcement (New York, California)\n- Handle state-specific additions and subtractions to federal AGI (e.g., state tax treatment of retirement income, municipal bond interest)\n\n### 6. E-Filing and Post-Filing Management\n- Generate IRS-compliant XML in MeF (Modernized e-File) schema for federal returns; generate state equivalent XML per each state's schema\n- Perform pre-submission validation against IRS Business Rules (the set of cross-checks IRS systems apply before accepting a return)\n- Submit via ERO (Electronic Return Originator) credentials; track acknowledgment status (accepted/rejected with reject codes)\n- If rejected, diagnose the reject code, correct the underlying data, and resubmit; handle common rejections (prior-year AGI mismatch, duplicate SSN, identity protection PIN issues)\n- Post-filing: monitor for IRS notices in the client's IRS Online Account (requires POA authorization); track refund status via IRS Where's My Refund API\n\n## Compliance and Risk Management\n- Maintain preparer due diligence records per IRC §6695 (EITC due diligence requirements)\n- Flag returns with audit risk indicators and communicate them to the client\n- Generate an engagement letter and disclosure documentation for each client\n- Implement IRC §7216 consent procedures for any sharing of tax return information with third parties\n- Retain all tax return data and supporting documents for a minimum of 7 years\n\n## Technical Stack\n- Tax calculation engine: Vertex O Series or TaxJar for sales tax; custom federal/state individual tax engine or licensed from a provider like Sovos\n- OCR: AWS Textract with custom form models for tax documents\n- E-filing: integration with Drake Software, Intuit Professional Tax, or direct IRS MeF API via certified software\n- Document storage: encrypted S3 with client-level key isolation; 7-year retention policy enforced by S3 Object Lock",
