    "title": "Environmental Compliance Monitoring Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Environmental Compliance Monitoring Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nAn Environmental Compliance Monitoring Agent continuously tracks industrial facilities' adherence to environmental regulations — covering air emissions, water discharge, hazardous waste management, and reporting obligations. It integrates sensor data, regulatory databases, and permit conditions to provide real-time compliance status and automated reporting. This blueprint covers the design of a proactive compliance agent for regulated industrial facilities.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Permit Registry and Obligation Mapping\nThe foundation of the agent is a structured registry of all environmental permits held by the facility:\n- **Air permits**: Title V or minor source permits under the Clean Air Act; track each emission limit by pollutant, averaging period (hourly, daily, annual), and applicable test method\n- **NPDES permits**: National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System permits for wastewater and stormwater discharge; map each outfall, its effluent limits, monitoring frequency, and required test methods\n- **RCRA permits**: Resource Conservation and Recovery Act hazardous waste treatment, storage, or disposal permits; track unit-specific conditions and inspection frequency requirements\n- **State and local permits**: air quality district permits, state water permits, noise ordinances, land use conditions\n\nFor each permit condition, create a structured obligation record: what must be measured, how often, by what method, what the limit is, and when/where it must be reported. This obligation map is the source of truth for all subsequent monitoring and reporting activities.\n\n### 2. Real-Time Emissions and Discharge Monitoring\nIntegrate with the facility's CEMS (Continuous Emissions Monitoring Systems) and process instrumentation:\n- Poll CEMS data (typically via OPC-UA or PI historian integration) at the native data collection frequency (usually 15-second or 1-minute intervals)\n- Apply QA/QC protocols per 40 CFR Part 75 or the applicable performance specification: flag and substitute missing data per the applicable missing data substitution procedures, identify and handle data quality flags\n- Calculate rolling averages at each required averaging period: 1-hour, 3-hour, 24-hour, 30-day rolling, quarterly, annual\n- Compare calculated averages against permit limits and trigger alerts at configurable thresholds: warning at 85% of limit, alarm at 100%, exceedance documented immediately\n\nFor water discharge monitoring:\n- Integrate with SCADA systems or manual laboratory LIMS for effluent sample results\n- Track sample timing compliance (samples must be taken within the correct time window relative to discharge events)\n- Calculate flow-weighted composite concentrations where required by the permit\n\n### 3. Hazardous Waste Tracking\nImplement a full hazardous waste manifest system:\n- Track waste generation by waste stream (using EPA waste codes and state-specific codes)\n- Apply the generator status calculation: sum waste generated per calendar month; determine if the facility is a Very Small Quantity Generator (VSQG), Small Quantity Generator (SQG), or Large Quantity Generator (LQG) — status determines accumulation time limits and other requirements\n- Issue alerts when accumulation time limits are approaching (LQG: 90 days; SQG: 270 days)\n- Manage electronic manifest (e-Manifest) creation, routing to transporters, and tracking through disposal facility signature\n- Track annual waste generation totals for Biennial Report preparation (due March 1 in odd years)\n\n### 4. Automated Compliance Reporting\nGenerate all required regulatory reports:\n- **EPA Emissions Inventory** (annual, due to state agency, typically March): calculate annual mass emissions for all criteria pollutants and HAPs using AP-42 emission factors or CEMS data; format for the applicable electronic reporting system (CAERS for large facilities)\n- **DMR (Discharge Monitoring Reports)**: compile effluent monitoring results for each reporting period; calculate averages, maximums, and exceedances; submit via NetDMR (EPA's electronic DMR system)\n- **TRI (Toxic Release Inventory) reporting**: calculate releases and transfers of listed chemicals above reporting thresholds; submit Form R or Form A via EPA's TRI-MEweb system by July 1\n- **State-specific reports**: many states require more frequent or more detailed reports than federal minimums; encode state-specific formats and submission requirements\n\nAll reports are generated from the validated monitoring data and include a complete audit trail showing source data, calculation methodology, and QA review.\n\n### 5. Inspection Preparedness\nThe agent maintains a continuous inspection readiness posture:\n- **Regulatory activity monitoring**: subscribe to EPA ECHO (Enforcement and Compliance History Online) updates and state agency docket systems to track any inspections, notices of violation, or enforcement actions affecting the facility or similar facilities in the sector\n- **Record availability**: maintain an indexed archive of all monitoring records, calibration records, maintenance logs, training records, and reports with rapid retrieval capability — regulators typically have the right to request records within hours during an inspection\n- **Compliance gap assessment**: run weekly self-audits comparing current operational data against all permit conditions; flag deviations with estimated regulatory risk (de minimis exceedance vs. significant violation)\n- **Deviation reporting preparation**: when an exceedance occurs, the agent drafts the required deviation report (most air permits require prompt notification within 2 business days and a written report within 30 days)\n\n### 6. Environmental Management System (EMS) Integration\nThe agent integrates with ISO 14001 EMS elements:\n- Track corrective actions from internal audits, agency inspections, and incident investigations through to completion\n- Manage environmental objectives and targets with progress tracking\n- Schedule and track required operator training and certification renewals\n- Maintain the aspect/impact register with links to relevant permit conditions\n\n## Technical Architecture\n- **Data integration**: OSIsoft PI for CEMS historian; OPC-UA for real-time DCS/SCADA integration; LIMS API integration for laboratory results\n- **Calculation engine**: rule-based calculation engine executing permit-specific calculations with complete audit trails; all calculation logic versioned to match applicable regulatory guidance\n- **Alert management**: tiered alerting via PagerDuty (exceedances) and email/Slack (approaching limits, upcoming deadlines)\n- **Document management**: immutable storage in S3 with 10-year retention; full-text search for inspection readiness\n\n## Regulatory Coverage\nPrimary regulations addressed: Clean Air Act (40 CFR Parts 51, 60, 63, 70, 72, 75), Clean Water Act (40 CFR Parts 122-125, 136), RCRA (40 CFR Parts 260-279), EPCRA (40 CFR Parts 355, 370, 372), TSCA.",
