    "title": "Intellectual Property Search Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Intellectual Property Search Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nAn Intellectual Property Search Agent automates patent, trademark, and copyright searches to support freedom-to-operate analysis, clearance searches, prior art discovery, and IP portfolio management. This blueprint covers the search architecture, database integrations, analysis workflows, and reporting patterns needed to build a reliable IP intelligence agent for legal and R&D teams.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Patent Search and Retrieval\nThe agent connects to global patent databases to perform comprehensive prior art and FTO searches:\n\n**Database Integrations:**\n- **USPTO Patent Full-Text and Image Database** (PatFT/AppFT): full-text search via USPTO Open Data Portal API\n- **EPO Espacenet / OPS API**: European Patent Office Open Patent Services API for EP, PCT, and 100+ national authority collections\n- **Google Patents API**: broad coverage with machine learning enhanced search\n- **Lens.org API**: open access patent database with citation analytics\n- **Derwent Innovation** (via subscription): enhanced patent database with value-added indexing\n\n**Search Strategy Engine:**\nThe agent implements a systematic search strategy rather than ad hoc keyword queries:\n1. Concept decomposition: break the technology into functional components (e.g., \"wireless glucose monitor\" → [wireless communication methods] AND [glucose sensing mechanisms] AND [wearable form factors])\n2. Claim term expansion: use the USPTO Gene Ontology and technology thesauri to identify synonyms and related terms; apply truncation and wildcard operators systematically\n3. Classification-based search: identify the most relevant CPC (Cooperative Patent Classification) subgroups and search within them — classification search catches patents that use different terminology for the same concept\n4. Citation mining: for highly relevant documents found in keyword/classification searches, forward-cite (who cited this?) and backward-cite (what does this cite?) to map the technology landscape\n\nTrack all search queries executed, result counts, and relevance assessments to support the required search strategy documentation for FTO opinions.\n\n### 2. Trademark Clearance Search\nFor trademark clearance, the agent performs a multi-database, multi-factor search:\n\n**Databases searched:**\n- USPTO TESS (Trademark Electronic Search System) via Trademark Status API\n- EU Intellectual Property Office (EUIPO) eSearch\n- WIPO Global Brand Database (covering 100+ national trademark offices)\n- State trademark registries (50 states via individual state SOS portals)\n- Common law sources: business name databases, domain registrations (WHOIS), major e-commerce platforms, social media handles\n\n**Similarity Analysis:**\nBeyond exact and phonetic matches (Soundex, Double Metaphone algorithms), the agent evaluates:\n- Visual similarity for design marks (using perceptual hash comparison of mark images)\n- Conceptual similarity (a search for \"SUNRISE\" should surface marks like \"DAYBREAK\" if used on similar goods)\n- International Class overlap for goods/services covered\n- Likelihood of confusion factors per the DuPont factors framework\n\nOutput a clearance opinion matrix scoring the searched mark against each potentially conflicting reference on each DuPont factor.\n\n### 3. Freedom-to-Operate (FTO) Analysis\nFTO analysis requires determining whether a proposed product or process would infringe any unexpired patent claims in the target markets:\n- Filter patent search results to in-force patents only (verify maintenance fee payment status via USPTO PAIR or national office status APIs)\n- Identify the relevant independent claims from each potentially relevant patent\n- Map product/process features to claim elements — flag any claim where every limitation appears to be present in the proposed design (all-elements rule)\n- For method claims, verify that all steps are performed within the jurisdiction (extraterritorial acts generally do not constitute infringement)\n- Evaluate claim scope using file wrapper prosecution history (retrieve from Patent Center API) — arguments made during prosecution may narrow the claim scope beyond the literal language\n\nThe agent generates a claim chart matrix for each patent identified as a potential concern, with each column representing a claim element and each row representing the proposed product feature being evaluated.\n\n### 4. IP Portfolio Management\nFor organizations with their own IP portfolios:\n- Track patent family members across jurisdictions; display a consolidated view of protection by country\n- Monitor annuity and maintenance fee payment deadlines with 12-month and 6-month advance alerts (missed maintenance fees cause patent abandonment)\n- Track prosecution status for pending applications: office actions received, response deadlines, notice of allowances\n- Calculate portfolio strength metrics: citation frequency, forward citation growth rate, technology coverage vs. competitor portfolios\n- Monitor competitor patent activity in defined technology spaces using assignee-based watch searches executed monthly\n\n### 5. Competitive Intelligence and Patent Landscaping\nThe agent generates technology landscape reports for strategic planning:\n- Identify the major patent filers in a technology space using assignee analytics\n- Map technology sub-areas using CPC classification cluster analysis\n- Identify white spaces — technology concepts addressed in the literature but with sparse patent coverage\n- Track patent expiration timelines to identify when key blocking patents will expire and become freely available\n- Monitor published patent applications from key competitors for early-warning intelligence on their R&D directions\n\n### 6. Copyright and Trade Secret Considerations\nBeyond patents and trademarks:\n- **Copyright clearance**: for software, literature, and creative works, check Copyright Office registration database and verify ownership chains\n- **Open source license compliance**: scan software codebases for open source components using SPDX-standard SBOMs or tools like FOSSA; flag GPL/AGPL components in proprietary products that create copyleft obligations\n- **Trade secret protection assessment**: evaluate whether technical information qualifies for trade secret protection and whether adequate reasonable measures are in place (access controls, NDAs, confidentiality policies)\n\n## Technical Architecture\n- Search orchestration: parallel query dispatch to multiple database APIs with result deduplication based on patent publication number\n- NLP layer: claim parsing and element extraction using a legal NLP model fine-tuned on patent claim syntax; entity recognition for technical terms\n- Similarity scoring: TF-IDF and BM25 for keyword relevance; sentence transformers for semantic similarity; custom models for trademark visual comparison\n- Output: structured claim charts in Excel/Google Sheets export; executive summary PDF; raw data in JSON for further analysis",
