    "title": "Content Moderation Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Content Moderation Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nA Content Moderation Agent automatically reviews user-generated content — text, images, videos, and audio — to detect and act on policy violations including hate speech, harassment, spam, misinformation, CSAM, and coordinated inauthentic behavior. This blueprint covers the multi-layer detection architecture, human review workflows, appeals handling, and transparency reporting required for a production moderation system.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Multi-Modal Content Ingestion\nThe agent processes content across all media types submitted to the platform:\n- **Text**: user posts, comments, messages, usernames, profile bios — tokenize and process through text classifiers\n- **Images**: extract metadata (EXIF data for geolocation and device information), run perceptual hash matching against known CSAM and terrorist content hash databases (PhotoDNA integration), apply computer vision classifiers for nudity/violence/gore/drug content\n- **Video**: sample frames at regular intervals plus detect scene boundaries for analysis; extract and process audio track separately; check against video hash databases\n- **Audio**: transcribe speech to text for content policy review; detect non-speech audio markers (gunshots, screaming) that may indicate harmful content in videos\n\nContent submitted to the agent carries a content source context object: platform surface (public feed, private message, story, comment), author account metadata (account age, prior violation history, follower count, verification status), and geographic origin (for jurisdiction-specific content regulations).\n\n### 2. Automated Detection Layer\nApply a cascade of detection models optimized for different violation categories:\n\n**Tier 1 — Hash Matching (near-zero latency):**\nApply perceptual hashing (pHash, PhotoDNA) to detect exact or near-exact copies of content in known-bad databases. This catches known CSAM and known terrorist recruitment content with high precision before any ML inference is needed.\n\n**Tier 2 — Keyword and Pattern Matching:**\nApply a curated blocklist for unambiguous violations (known slurs, specific prohibited phrases) and regex patterns for spam signals (URLs with high abuse rates, known phishing domains, repetitive content patterns). Execute in milliseconds.\n\n**Tier 3 — ML Classifiers:**\n- Text: transformer-based classifiers for hate speech, harassment, self-harm promotion, spam, misinformation; output probability scores per category\n- Image: CNN-based classifiers for nudity (with granular adult content vs. medical vs. artistic context), graphic violence, dangerous products, symbols associated with hate groups\n- Multi-modal: cross-modal models that analyze text and image together — the same image can be benign or policy-violating depending on the accompanying caption\n\n**Tier 4 — LLM Context Analysis:**\nFor borderline cases where the classifier confidence is in the ambiguous range, use a large language model with the platform's content policy as context to reason about whether the content violates policy. This is slower and more expensive but catches nuanced violations that simpler classifiers miss (e.g., coded language, sarcasm-disguised harassment).\n\n### 3. Policy Enforcement Actions\nWhen a violation is detected with confidence above the enforcement threshold:\n- **Content removal**: soft delete (hides from public but preserves for appeal evidence) vs. hard delete (for CSAM — required by NCMEC reporting obligations)\n- **User warning**: notify the user that content was removed and cite the specific policy violated; provide a link to the full policy\n- **Account restrictions**: temporary suspension of posting privileges, rate limiting, demotion in distribution algorithms, removal of monetization access\n- **Account termination**: for severe or repeat violations; preserve account data for potential law enforcement requests\n- **Reporting to authorities**: mandatory NCMEC CyberTipline reporting for any CSAM; optional reporting to law enforcement for imminent threats to safety (active shooter, suicide in progress — coordinate with crisis line partners)\n\nImplement a sanctions escalation policy: first violation = warning; second = 24-hour posting suspension; third = 7-day suspension; fourth = permanent suspension (with category-specific overrides — CSAM is always immediate permanent ban and reporting).\n\n### 4. Human Review Queue Management\nMany moderation decisions require human judgment. The agent manages a tiered review queue:\n- **Priority routing**: route content involving imminent safety threats (suicide, violence) to a 24/7 on-call team; route CSAM detection flags to a specially trained and trauma-informed team; route political speech and news content to a team with specialized policy training\n- **Reviewer assignment**: match content language to reviewer language proficiency; distribute review load across time zones to meet response SLAs\n- **Context packaging**: present reviewers with the content, account history, prior violations, and the automated analysis rationale — do not pre-bias reviewers with the automated decision, but provide the evidence\n- **Quality assurance**: blind secondary review a sample of 5% of moderator decisions to assess inter-rater reliability; provide feedback to reviewers whose decisions deviate significantly from calibration standards\n\n### 5. Appeals Processing\nUsers whose content is removed or accounts are suspended have a right to appeal:\n- Generate automated appeal forms pre-populated with the policy citation and removal reason\n- Apply a separate review model to evaluate whether the original moderation decision was correct given the full context\n- Route appeals to a senior moderation team independent of the original reviewer\n- Meet jurisdiction-specific appeals resolution timelines (EU DSA requires timely resolution)\n- Track appeal overturn rates by violation category and reviewer team — high overturn rates signal a calibration problem requiring retraining or policy clarification\n\n### 6. Transparency and Compliance Reporting\nRegulatory frameworks (EU DSA, UK Online Safety Act, various national laws) require periodic transparency reporting:\n- Track total content actioned, breakdown by violation type and action taken, error rates (content removed then restored on appeal)\n- Generate Transparency Reports at required intervals (typically semi-annual for DSA-covered platforms)\n- Maintain records of all automated enforcement decisions for regulatory audit purposes\n- Publish policy change notices with the effective date and rationale\n\n## Technical Architecture\n- Orchestration: event-driven pipeline (Kafka) where each piece of content submission triggers the moderation cascade\n- Model serving: ONNX Runtime or TorchServe for low-latency classifier inference; separate GPU cluster for LLM-based context analysis\n- Hash database: Microsoft PhotoDNA integration for CSAM; GIFCT hash sharing database for terrorist content\n- Human review tooling: Perspective API for reviewer assistance; custom review interface with keyboard shortcuts for efficient review throughput (target: 200-400 items per reviewer per hour for Tier 1 decisions)\n- Appeals management: ticketing system integration (Zendesk or custom) with SLA tracking",
