    "memory_id": "ghm_084",
    "title": "Energy Trading Agent Blueprint",
    "category": "industry_blueprints",
    "content": "`# Energy Trading Agent Blueprint\n\n## Overview\nAn Energy Trading Agent automates the analysis, decision-making, and execution of energy commodity trades — including electricity, natural gas, crude oil, and renewable energy certificates (RECs). It integrates with market data feeds, grid operator systems, and risk management platforms to execute trades within defined risk parameters while optimizing the portfolio's economic performance. This blueprint covers the full stack from market data ingestion through trade execution, position management, and regulatory reporting.\n\n## Core Capabilities\n\n### 1. Market Data Integration and Signal Generation\nThe agent requires comprehensive real-time and historical market data:\n\n**Power markets:**\n- **ISO/RTO real-time data**: connect to the APIs of ISO-NE, NYISO, PJM, MISO, CAISO, ERCOT, and SPP for real-time and day-ahead locational marginal prices (LMPs), ancillary services prices, and load/generation data\n- **Forward curve data**: subscribe to broker OTC price feeds (ICE, CME) for forward electricity and natural gas prices at relevant hubs (Henry Hub, Dominion South, Algonquin, TETCO M3, PJM West, CAISO SP15)\n- **Fundamental data**: natural gas storage reports (EIA Weekly Natural Gas Storage Report, published Thursdays 10:30 AM ET), power demand forecasts, renewable generation forecasts (wind and solar from NREL/Solargis APIs), plant outage data from NERC generators outage reports\n\n**Commodity markets:**\n- CME Group API for NYMEX Henry Hub natural gas, WTI crude, and associated options chains\n- ICE Endex for European gas and power benchmarks\n- RECs: PJM-EIS GATS and other REC tracking system APIs for REC spot and forward prices\n\nGenerate trading signals from multiple analytical methods:\n- **Statistical arbitrage**: identify mean-reverting spreads between correlated price series (spark spread = power price minus heat rate × gas price; dark spread for coal markets)\n- **Fundamental models**: correlate weather forecast deviations from normal (heating/cooling degree days) with expected demand and price impacts\n- **Technical signals**: momentum indicators (RSI, MACD) and breakout signals on liquid forward contracts for systematic trend-following strategies\n- **Event-driven signals**: EIA inventory surprises, FERC regulatory decisions, major plant outage announcements\n\n### 2. Portfolio Optimization and Position Management\nThe agent optimizes the portfolio of open positions across the trading book:\n- **Mark-to-market valuation**: value all open positions at current market prices in real time; compute unrealized P&L and update position risk metrics continuously\n- **Greeks calculation**: for options positions, calculate delta, gamma, vega, and theta; maintain delta-neutral positions if the trading strategy requires it through dynamic hedging\n- **VaR and CVaR computation**: calculate Value at Risk at the 95% and 99% confidence levels using Monte Carlo simulation with appropriate price process assumptions (mean-reverting for power, random walk for oil and gas); compare against approved trading limits\n- **Correlation-adjusted portfolio risk**: account for correlations between positions — a long power/short gas position has partially offsetting risks in volatile periods\n\nEnforce risk limits at multiple levels: per-trade size limits, per-commodity position limits, overall portfolio VaR limit, and loss limits (daily P&L stop-loss triggers immediate position liquidation protocol).\n\n### 3. Day-Ahead and Real-Time Market Participation\nFor electricity markets, the agent manages the bidding process:\n\n**Day-ahead market (DAM):**\n- Forecast the next day's hourly load profile using weather forecasts + historical consumption patterns\n- Optimize the asset dispatch schedule: for generation assets, determine the economic dispatch across the fleet considering start-up costs, ramp constraints, minimum run times, and heat rates; for load, determine optimal curtailment offers\n- Submit hourly energy, capacity, and ancillary services bids/offers to the ISO by the DAM close (typically 10:00-12:00 AM local time day-ahead)\n- Track DAM clearing results via ISO API; capture cleared quantities and prices for scheduling and settlement purposes\n\n**Real-time market:**\n- Monitor the real-time dispatch instructions from the ISO Automatic Generation Control (AGC) signal\n- Respond to economic dispatch signals within the required ramp rate capabilities\n- Identify and execute intra-hour trading opportunities when real-time prices diverge significantly from day-ahead prices\n\n### 4. Natural Gas Scheduling and Nominations\nFor gas-consuming assets (power plants) or gas marketing positions:\n- Calculate daily burn forecasts for gas-fired generation based on the day-ahead dispatch schedule\n- Submit gas nominations to pipeline operators by the Timely Nomination Cycle deadline (10:00 AM CCT) and subsequent cycles as needed\n- Monitor intraday nominations and adjust as dispatch schedules change\n- Track gas imbalances (actual consumption vs. nominated volumes) and manage within pipeline tolerance bands to avoid imbalance penalties\n\n### 5. Trade Execution and Order Management\nWhen the agent's models generate a trade signal and risk checks pass:\n- **Execution logic**: determine optimal execution strategy — aggressive market order for liquid instruments, limit order for less liquid OTC products to minimize market impact\n- **Counterparty selection**: for OTC bilateral trades, select counterparty based on credit rating, available credit line (Credit Support Annex/CSA terms), and current bid/offer spreads\n- **ISDA documentation**: verify that an executed ISDA Master Agreement and applicable Schedule/CSA are in place with the counterparty before executing any OTC derivative\n- **Trade confirmation**: generate trade confirms via DTCC's ICE Trade Vault for cleared products; via email or Bloomberg messaging for bilateral OTC; record all trade details in ETRM system\n\n### 6. Settlement, Accounting, and Regulatory Reporting\nPost-trade lifecycle management:\n- **Physical settlement**: for physical delivery contracts, coordinate nomination, scheduling, and transportation arrangements; track delivery performance and resolve quantity/quality disputes\n- **Financial settlement**: calculate monthly settlement amounts for financially settled contracts; generate payment instructions and reconcile against counterparty confirms\n- **FERC/CFTC reporting**: energy commodity derivatives traded in the US are subject to Dodd-Frank reporting obligations for swaps; submit trade reports to DTCC's SDR via SFTP in FIXML format within the required reporting window (T+1 for swaps)\n- **P&L attribution**: decompose daily P&L into components — price change impact, new trade P&L, time decay for options, settlements received/paid\n\n## Technical Architecture\n- Market data: Bloomberg API (B-PIPE) or Refinitiv Eikon API for commodity prices; ISO market portals for grid data\n- ETRM system: Openlink Endur, Brady (formerly Triple Point), or Aucerna for trade capture and position management\n- Risk engine: internal or Murex/Calypso for real-time risk calculations\n- Execution: direct API integration with exchange platforms (ICE, CME Globex) for exchange-traded products; Bloomberg TSOX for OTC execution\n- Infrastructure: low-latency compute environment (co-location with exchange data centers for HFT applications); primary-secondary failover for business continuity\n\n## Risk Governance\nThe agent operates within a governance framework:\n- All trading strategies require pre-approval by the Risk Committee with defined position limits and stop-loss parameters\n- Model risk management: all pricing and forecasting models undergo independent validation before deployment\n- Audit trail: all trade decisions, model outputs, and risk overrides are logged immutably for regulatory examination",
