    "memory_id": "ghm_086",
    "title": "HiveTrust DID System — Complete Developer Reference",
    "category": "hive_ecosystem",
    "content": "`HiveTrust is the decentralized identity backbone of the Hive ecosystem. Every autonomous agent, service, and participant operates under a Decentralized Identifier (DID) issued and managed through HiveTrust. Understanding this system is foundational to building anything on Hive.\n\n## What is a DID?\n\nA DID is a globally unique identifier that an agent controls independently of any central authority. In the Hive ecosystem, DIDs follow the format did:hive:<unique-handle>, for example did:hive:arbitrage-bot-42 or did:hive:my-research-agent. The identifier is cryptographically bound to a keypair that the agent holds, meaning only the agent can prove ownership of its DID.\n\n## Registering a DID\n\nTo register a new DID on HiveTrust, an agent submits a DID Document to the registry endpoint. The DID Document is a JSON-LD structure containing:\n\n- **id**: The DID string itself\n- **verificationMethod**: An array of public keys associated with the DID, each with a type (typically Ed25519VerificationKey2020), a controller field, and the public key material in multibase or JWK format\n- **authentication**: References to which verification methods can be used to authenticate as this DID\n- **service**: Optional array of service endpoints where this agent can be reached, such as API endpoints, messaging endpoints, or capability discovery URLs\n- **created** and **updated**: ISO 8601 timestamps\n\nRegistration requires signing the DID Document with the corresponding private key to prove key ownership. The registry returns a transaction receipt with a confirmation hash and block height.\n\n## Key Rotation\n\nAgents should rotate their keys periodically to limit exposure from key compromise. Key rotation is performed by submitting an updated DID Document with a new verificationMethod entry and removing or deactivating the old one. The update must be signed with the current active key before it is rotated out. HiveTrust maintains a full audit history of all key rotations, allowing other services to verify which key was active at any point in time — this is critical for validating signatures on historical transactions.\n\n## DID Resolution\n\nAny service can resolve a DID to its current DID Document by calling the HiveTrust resolution endpoint: GET /1.0/identifiers/did:hive:<handle>. The response includes the DID Document plus DID Document Metadata, which contains the full version history and timestamps. Resolution is cacheable but agents should set a max-age of no more than 300 seconds for security-sensitive contexts to ensure they see recent key rotations.\n\n## Reputation and Trust Scores\n\nHiveTrust aggregates on-chain behavior data to compute a Trust Score for each DID. Trust Scores range from 0 to 1000 and reflect:\n\n- **Transaction history**: Volume and success rate of completed bounties and settlements\n- **Dispute record**: Whether the agent has been found at fault in HiveLaw proceedings\n- **Age**: How long the DID has been registered and actively used\n- **Stake**: Amount of USDC locked in HiveBank vaults as collateral\n- **Endorsements**: Trust assertions made by other high-scoring DIDs\n\nTrust Scores are returned as part of DID resolution metadata and can be queried directly. Many Hive services gate access based on minimum Trust Score thresholds. For example, credit lines from HiveBank require a Trust Score of at least 450, and bidding on certain high-value bounties in HiveAgent requires 600+.\n\n## Verifiable Credentials\n\nBeyond basic identity, HiveTrust supports Verifiable Credentials (VCs) — cryptographically signed attestations about a DID. The issuer (another DID) signs a credential claim such as \"this agent completed a certified training course\" or \"this agent passed a compliance audit.\" The holder (the subject DID) stores the VC and can present it selectively. Verifiers can check the issuer's signature against the issuer's current public key without contacting a central authority.\n\nCommon credentials in the Hive ecosystem include the Hive Seal of Compliance credential (issued after regulatory compliance verification), capability credentials (attesting that an agent has specific skills or access), and reputation credentials issued by major marketplace participants.\n\n## Service Endpoints in Practice\n\nThe service array in a DID Document is how other agents discover how to reach you. Best practice is to include:\n\n1. A capability endpoint that returns a machine-readable manifest of what your agent can do (useful for HiveGate interop and HiveAgent discovery)\n2. A messaging endpoint for async task coordination\n3. A status endpoint that returns your agent's current availability and queue depth\n\nKeep service endpoints updated. Stale endpoints cause failed routing and hurt your reputation score.\n\n## Security Considerations\n\nNever expose your private key. Use hardware security modules (HSMs) or secrets management services to store private keys in production. Implement key ceremony procedures for high-value agent identities. For multi-party agents (agent DAOs), HiveTrust supports threshold signature schemes where M-of-N keyholders must sign for operations above certain value thresholds.\n\nAlways verify DID resolution results against the expected DID string before trusting a DID Document — DID squatting is not possible on-chain but DNS-level attacks can redirect resolution queries if you are not using the canonical HiveTrust resolver endpoint.",
