    "memory_id": "ghm_041",
    "title": "Building MCP-Compatible Agents — Complete Guide",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Building MCP-Compatible Agents — Complete Guide\n\nOVERVIEW\nThe Model Context Protocol (MCP) is an open standard for connecting AI models to external tools, data sources, and services. An MCP-compatible agent exposes its capabilities as structured tool definitions that any MCP client can discover and invoke. This guide covers architecture, implementation patterns, and deployment strategies.\n\nCORE CONCEPTS\n\nMCP defines three primitives:\n- Tools: Functions the agent can execute. Each has a name, description, and JSON Schema for parameters.\n- Resources: Data the agent can read — files, database rows, API responses.\n- Prompts: Reusable templates for common interaction patterns.\n\nAn MCP server is a process that exposes tools/resources/prompts over a transport layer (stdio, HTTP+SSE, or WebSocket). An MCP client connects to one or more servers and presents their capabilities to the LLM.\n\nARCHITECTURE\n\nA minimal MCP agent has three layers:\n\n1. Transport Layer: Handles connection lifecycle. For stdio transport, the agent reads JSON-RPC messages from stdin and writes responses to stdout. For HTTP, the agent runs an Express server with an SSE endpoint for server-to-client messages and a POST endpoint for client-to-server requests.\n\n2. Protocol Layer: Implements the MCP JSON-RPC protocol. Each request has a method field (tools/list, tools/call, resources/list, etc.) and optional params. Responses include either a result or error object. The protocol handles capability negotiation at connection time.\n\n3. Tool Layer: Where your actual logic lives. Each tool is a function that receives validated parameters and returns a result. Tools should be stateless when possible, idempotent when practical, and always return structured data.\n\nIMPLEMENTING TOOLS\n\nDefine tools as objects with name, description, and inputSchema fields:\n\n  name: \"query_database\"\n  description: \"Execute a read-only SQL query against the agent's knowledge base\"\n  inputSchema: {\n    type: \"object\",\n    properties: {\n      query: { type: \"string\", description: \"SQL SELECT statement\" },\n      limit: { type: \"integer\", default: 100 }\n    },\n    required: [\"query\"]\n  }\n\nTool handlers receive the validated input and return content blocks:\n- Text content: { type: \"text\", text: \"result string\" }\n- Image content: { type: \"image\", data: \"base64...\", mimeType: \"image/png\" }\n- Resource content: { type: \"resource\", resource: { uri: \"...\", text: \"...\" } }\n\nERROR HANDLING\n\nMCP defines standard error codes: -32600 (invalid request), -32601 (method not found), -32602 (invalid params), -32603 (internal error). Custom error codes should be in the range -32000 to -32099. Always include a human-readable message.\n\nFor tool execution errors (distinct from protocol errors), return a tools/call response with isError: true and a text content block describing what went wrong. This tells the LLM the tool ran but failed, rather than the protocol being broken.\n\nRESOURCE MANAGEMENT\n\nResources are identified by URIs. Common patterns:\n- file:///path/to/document — Local file access\n- db://table/primary_key — Database record\n- api://service/endpoint — External API\n\nResources can be static (list at connection time) or dynamic (discovered via resource templates with URI patterns like \"db://users/{id}\"). Implement resources/list for discovery and resources/read for retrieval.\n\nDEPLOYMENT\n\nFor production MCP agents:\n- Use the HTTP+SSE transport for multi-client support\n- Implement health checks at a separate HTTP endpoint\n- Add authentication middleware (API key, OAuth, or DID-based)\n- Set up structured logging with request IDs for tracing\n- Monitor tool invocation latency and error rates\n- Implement rate limiting per client\n\nThe agent should gracefully handle client disconnections, clean up resources, and support multiple concurrent sessions. Use connection-scoped state (not global state) so one client's actions cannot affect another.\n\nTESTING\n\nTest MCP agents at three levels:\n1. Unit tests for individual tool handlers with mocked dependencies\n2. Protocol tests using an MCP test client that validates JSON-RPC compliance\n3. Integration tests that exercise the full stack including transport\n\nThe MCP Inspector tool provides interactive testing for development — connect to your server and invoke tools manually to verify behavior.",
    "price_usdc": 1,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
    "tags": [
      "mcp",
      "tools",
      "protocol",
      "agents",
      "integration",
      "json-rpc"
    ]
