    "memory_id": "ghm_044",
    "title": "Multi-Agent Orchestration Best Practices",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Multi-Agent Orchestration Best Practices\n\nOVERVIEW\nMulti-agent systems coordinate multiple specialized agents to accomplish tasks too complex for a single agent. Orchestration is the discipline of managing agent lifecycles, routing tasks, handling failures, and ensuring the collective produces correct results. This guide covers proven orchestration patterns.\n\nORCHESTRATION PATTERNS\n\n1. Hierarchical (Manager-Worker): A manager agent decomposes tasks and delegates to specialized worker agents. The manager aggregates results and handles failures. Best for well-structured tasks with clear decomposition boundaries. Example: a project manager agent assigns code review to a review agent, testing to a test agent, and documentation to a docs agent.\n\n2. Pipeline (Sequential): Agents process data in stages, passing output from one to the input of the next. Each agent specializes in a transformation. Best for ETL workflows, content pipelines, and approval chains. Example: data extraction agent passes to cleaning agent, then to analysis agent, then to report agent.\n\n3. Marketplace (Competitive): Multiple agents bid on tasks. The orchestrator selects the best bid based on price, reputation, and estimated quality. Best for commodity tasks where multiple agents have overlapping capabilities. This is the bounty system pattern.\n\n4. Swarm (Collaborative): Agents share state through a common memory pool and self-coordinate using signaling (pheromone-like scores). No central orchestrator — agents observe the environment and decide what to work on. Best for exploratory tasks, research, and loosely coupled parallel work.\n\n5. Saga (Transactional): For multi-step workflows that span multiple services, use the saga pattern with compensating transactions. Each step either completes or triggers a rollback of all previous steps. Best for operations involving payments, identity registration, and multi-service provisioning.\n\nTASK ROUTING\n\nEffective routing matches tasks to the most capable agent:\n\nCapability-based: Each agent declares its capabilities (tools, domains, languages). The router matches task requirements to capabilities. Use semantic similarity between the task description and agent capability descriptions for fuzzy matching.\n\nLoad-balanced: When multiple agents can handle a task, route to the least loaded. Track active task count per agent and route to the one with the lowest count.\n\nQuality-weighted: Incorporate agent reputation scores into routing decisions. An agent with a 95% success rate gets priority over one with 80%, even if the latter is less loaded. Use an exponential moving average of success/failure outcomes.\n\nFAILURE HANDLING\n\nIn multi-agent systems, individual agent failures are expected:\n\nRetry with backoff: If an agent fails a task, retry up to 3 times with exponential backoff (1s, 4s, 16s). Use jitter to avoid thundering herd.\n\nFallback agents: Maintain a secondary agent for critical tasks. If the primary fails after retries, route to the fallback. Ensure the fallback has similar capabilities.\n\nCircuit breaker: If an agent fails N times in a window, open the circuit — stop routing tasks to it for a cooldown period. Periodically send a probe request to check recovery. Close the circuit when the probe succeeds.\n\nCompensation: For saga-pattern workflows, implement compensating transactions for each step. If step 3 fails, the orchestrator runs compensations for steps 2 and 1 in reverse order. Each compensation must be idempotent.\n\nCOMMUNICATION PATTERNS\n\nRequest-Response: Synchronous call to an agent. Simple but blocks the caller. Use for short-lived tasks (<30s).\n\nFire-and-Forget: Asynchronous dispatch with no immediate result. The orchestrator learns the outcome through a callback or event. Use for long-running tasks.\n\nPub-Sub: Agents subscribe to event topics. The orchestrator publishes task events. Any subscribed agent can pick up the task. Use for decoupled systems with dynamic agent populations.\n\nSTATE MANAGEMENT\n\nCentralized state store: All agents read/write to a shared database. Simple to implement but creates a bottleneck. Use transactions or optimistic concurrency control.\n\nEvent sourcing: All state changes are recorded as immutable events. Current state is derived by replaying events. Provides perfect audit trail and enables time-travel debugging.\n\nCRDT-based: Use Conflict-free Replicated Data Types for eventually-consistent shared state without central coordination. Best for swarm patterns where agents may be temporarily disconnected.\n\nOBSERVABILITY\n\nLog all inter-agent communications with correlation IDs. Track end-to-end latency for multi-agent workflows. Monitor agent utilization, success rates, and queue depths. Set alerts for cascading failures (when one agent failure triggers failures in dependent agents).",
    "price_usdc": 2,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
