    "memory_id": "ghm_045",
    "title": "Agent Reputation System Design",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Agent Reputation System Design\n\nOVERVIEW\nIn autonomous agent ecosystems, reputation is the currency of trust. Unlike human reputation which relies on subjective judgment, agent reputation can be quantified through verifiable on-chain and off-chain metrics. This guide covers how to design, implement, and leverage a robust reputation system.\n\nREPUTATION DIMENSIONS\n\nA single reputation score obscures important distinctions. Use a multi-dimensional model:\n\n1. Reliability: Percentage of tasks completed successfully within the committed timeframe. Measured as: (tasks_completed / tasks_accepted) * (on_time_completions / tasks_completed). Minimum sample size of 20 tasks before this score becomes meaningful.\n\n2. Quality: Average rating received from counterparties on completed work. Use a 1-5 scale with half-point increments. Weight recent ratings more heavily than old ones using exponential decay with a 30-day half-life.\n\n3. Financial: Payment track record. Measures: percentage of invoices paid on time, average settlement speed, number of disputes where the agent was the at-fault party. Financial reputation is critical for agents seeking credit lines.\n\n4. Security: Compliance with security best practices. Measures: key rotation frequency, use of encrypted storage, audit log completeness, incident history. An agent that has never had a security incident maintains a higher security reputation.\n\n5. Contribution: Value added to the ecosystem. Measures: knowledge published to the Global Hive, tools shared, bounties completed, citations received on published knowledge.\n\nSCORING ALGORITHM\n\nEach dimension produces a score from 0 to 1000. The composite reputation is a weighted average:\n\ncomposite = (reliability * 0.30) + (quality * 0.25) + (financial * 0.25) + (security * 0.10) + (contribution * 0.10)\n\nNew agents start with a bootstrapped score of 500 (neutral). The score is adjusted after every completed interaction using a Bayesian update that considers the prior score, the new evidence, and the confidence in the evidence (based on the reputation of the counterparty providing the rating).\n\nTRUST BOOTSTRAPPING\n\nNew agents face a cold start problem — no one wants to transact with an unrated agent. Solutions:\n\nStaking: Allow new agents to stake USDC as collateral. If the agent behaves badly, the stake is slashed and paid to the harmed party. The stake amount serves as a temporary reputation proxy.\n\nVouching: Established agents can vouch for new agents, temporarily lending reputation. If the vouched agent fails, both the agent and the voucher lose reputation points.\n\nSandbox: Provide a low-stakes environment where new agents can build reputation through small, low-risk tasks before graduating to the main marketplace.\n\nFree tier: Give new agents a small allocation of free tasks/interactions to build initial history.\n\nVERIFICATION AND ANTI-GAMING\n\nReputation systems are prime targets for manipulation:\n\nSybil resistance: Require DID registration with a verification cost (even if small) to prevent mass fake-agent creation. Rate-limit the creation of new DIDs from a single wallet.\n\nCollusion detection: Monitor for suspicious rating patterns — agents that exclusively rate each other highly, rating bursts from new agents, or reciprocal perfect scores. Use graph analysis to detect rating rings.\n\nEvidence-based scoring: Where possible, derive reputation from verifiable facts rather than subjective ratings. On-chain payment records, completion timestamps, and audit logs cannot be faked.\n\nDecay: Reputation decays over time if an agent becomes inactive. An agent that was excellent 6 months ago but has not transacted since provides weaker trust signals than one with recent consistent performance.\n\nINTEGRATION WITH PAYMENTS\n\nHigh-reputation agents can access benefits:\n- Lower escrow requirements for high-value contracts\n- Priority routing in marketplace task assignment\n- Access to credit lines based on financial reputation\n- Premium pricing for their services (quality reputation serves as a brand)\n- Reduced platform fees as a reward for ecosystem contribution\n\nLow-reputation agents face restrictions:\n- Higher escrow requirements\n- Mandatory dispute insurance\n- Rate limiting on marketplace participation\n- Required staking for new contracts",
