    "memory_id": "ghm_046",
    "title": "Autonomous Negotiation Protocol Design",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Autonomous Negotiation Protocol Design\n\nOVERVIEW\nWhen autonomous agents transact with each other, they need a structured negotiation protocol to agree on price, terms, quality, and deadlines without human intervention. This guide covers protocol design patterns for agent-to-agent negotiation.\n\nNEGOTIATION PHASES\n\nPhase 1 — Discovery: Agent A broadcasts a request (RFP) specifying what it needs. Available agents respond with capability declarations. This phase uses the marketplace's discovery mechanism.\n\nPhase 2 — Proposal: Responding agents submit structured proposals containing: proposed price, estimated completion time, quality guarantees, required inputs, and terms. Proposals conform to a standardized schema so Agent A can programmatically compare them.\n\nPhase 3 — Counter-offer: Agent A may counter-propose with different terms. Each counter-offer must reference the original proposal and specify what changed. The protocol allows up to N rounds of counter-offers (configurable, typically 3-5).\n\nPhase 4 — Agreement: Both parties sign the final terms. The agreement is hashed and stored on-chain (or in the settlement layer). This creates a verifiable contract.\n\nPhase 5 — Execution: Work proceeds per the agreement. Progress checkpoints may be built into the agreement for long-running tasks.\n\nPhase 6 — Settlement: Upon completion, the agreed payment is released. Disputes trigger the arbitration flow.\n\nPRICING STRATEGIES\n\nFixed price: The provider sets a non-negotiable price. Simplest approach, good for commodity services.\n\nDutch auction: Price starts high and decreases over time until an agent accepts. Good for urgent requests where speed matters more than cost.\n\nEnglish auction: Providers bid against each other, price goes up. Good when the buyer has high-value work and wants the best quality.\n\nBATNA-based: Each agent calculates its Best Alternative To Negotiated Agreement (the value of walking away). An agent only accepts deals better than its BATNA. This prevents agents from accepting unprofitable work.\n\nCost-plus: The provider calculates actual costs (compute, API calls, time) and adds a margin. Transparent and fair, but requires cost tracking infrastructure.\n\nPROTOCOL MESSAGE FORMAT\n\nNegotiation messages should be structured:\n\n  type: \"proposal\" | \"counter_offer\" | \"accept\" | \"reject\" | \"withdraw\"\n  proposal_id: unique identifier\n  parent_id: ID of the message being responded to (for counter-offers)\n  from_did: sender's DID\n  to_did: recipient's DID\n  terms:\n    price_usdc: proposed price\n    deadline: ISO 8601 timestamp\n    quality_sla: description of quality requirements\n    deliverables: list of expected outputs\n    escrow_required: boolean\n    dispute_arbitrator: DID of agreed arbitration service\n  valid_until: ISO 8601 timestamp (offer expiration)\n  signature: cryptographic signature by sender's DID key\n\nESCROW AND GUARANTEES\n\nFor high-value negotiations, use escrow:\n1. Buyer deposits the agreed amount into an escrow contract\n2. Provider can verify the deposit before starting work\n3. Upon completion and buyer acceptance, escrow releases to provider\n4. If disputed, the arbitrator controls release\n\nSmart escrow: Time-locked escrow that automatically releases to the provider after a deadline unless the buyer files a dispute. This prevents buyers from ghosting.\n\nMilestone-based: Large projects split payment into milestones. Each milestone has its own escrow. Partial delivery earns partial payment.\n\nTIMEOUT AND DEADLOCK HANDLING\n\nNegotiations can stall. Implement:\n- Offer expiration: Every proposal has a valid_until timestamp. Expired offers are automatically withdrawn.\n- Maximum rounds: Limit counter-offer rounds. After the limit, both parties must accept or reject.\n- Arbitrated deadlock: If agents cannot agree after maximum rounds, an arbitrator suggests fair terms based on market rates and both agents' histories.\n- Walk-away threshold: If the gap between positions exceeds a configurable threshold (e.g., 50% of the ask), auto-terminate to save time.",
