    "memory_id": "ghm_050",
    "title": "Scaling Agent Fleets — Infrastructure Patterns",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Scaling Agent Fleets — Infrastructure Patterns\n\nOVERVIEW\nA single agent is a service. A fleet of agents is a distributed system. Scaling from one agent to hundreds introduces challenges in resource management, coordination, state consistency, and cost control. This guide covers infrastructure patterns for running agent fleets at scale.\n\nFLEET ARCHITECTURE\n\nHub-and-Spoke: A central orchestrator manages all agents. Agents report status to the hub, receive task assignments, and submit results. The hub handles load balancing, failure detection, and scaling decisions. Simple to reason about but the hub is a single point of failure and potential bottleneck.\n\nMesh: Agents communicate directly with each other using a peer-to-peer protocol. Discovery through a gossip protocol or registry service. No central bottleneck but harder to monitor and debug.\n\nHybrid: A lightweight registry for discovery and health monitoring, combined with direct agent-to-agent communication for task execution. The registry is not on the critical path for task processing.\n\nCONTAINER ORCHESTRATION\n\nRun each agent as a container (Docker) orchestrated by Kubernetes:\n\nPod design: Each agent runs in its own pod with resource limits (CPU, memory). Use init containers for one-time setup (key generation, dependency installation). Use sidecars for cross-cutting concerns (logging, metrics, proxy).\n\nHorizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA): Scale the number of agent instances based on metrics — queue depth, response latency, or CPU utilization. Configure: minReplicas (always running), maxReplicas (cost ceiling), target metric threshold.\n\nStatefulSets: For agents that maintain local state (cached models, in-progress task context), use StatefulSets instead of Deployments. This gives each agent a stable identity and persistent volume.\n\nTASK QUEUE ARCHITECTURE\n\nUse a message queue (Redis Streams, RabbitMQ, or SQS) as the buffer between task submitters and agent workers:\n\n1. Task arrives and enters the queue with priority and deadline metadata.\n2. Idle agents pull tasks from the queue (competing consumers pattern).\n3. The agent processes the task and publishes the result to a result queue or callback URL.\n4. If the agent fails or times out, the message returns to the queue for retry.\n\nQueue configuration:\n- Visibility timeout: Set to 2x the expected maximum processing time. If the agent hasn't acknowledged completion by then, the message becomes available for another agent.\n- Dead letter queue: After N failed processing attempts, move the message to a DLQ for investigation.\n- Priority lanes: Use separate queues for different priority levels. High-priority tasks go to a queue that agents check first.\n\nCOST MANAGEMENT\n\nAgent fleets can become expensive quickly. Cost control mechanisms:\n\nSpot/preemptible instances: Run non-critical agents on spot instances at 60-80% cost savings. Implement checkpointing so agents can resume work after preemption.\n\nScale-to-zero: Agents that are idle for extended periods should be scaled down to zero replicas. Use event-driven scaling (KEDA) to spin up agents when tasks arrive in the queue.\n\nResource quotas: Set hard limits on total fleet resources to prevent runaway scaling. Each agent type gets a resource budget.\n\nCost attribution: Track compute costs per agent, per task type, and per customer. Use this data to price services appropriately and identify unprofitable work.\n\nSHARED STATE MANAGEMENT\n\nAgents need to share state (agent registry, reputation scores, memory indexes):\n\nRead-heavy state (agent capabilities, reputation): Use read replicas or a cache (Redis) with short TTL. Stale data is acceptable.\n\nWrite-heavy state (task assignments, payment records): Use a database with strong consistency. PostgreSQL with advisory locks for critical sections.\n\nEventually consistent state (usage metrics, aggregated stats): Use append-only logs (Kafka) with materialized views. Consumers can be minutes behind without issues.\n\nMONITORING AND ALERTING\n\nFleet-level dashboard:\n- Total agents running by type\n- Tasks processed per minute (throughput)\n- Queue depth and wait time\n- Error rate by agent type\n- Cost per task (compute + API calls)\n- Revenue per task\n\nAlerts:\n- Queue depth exceeds threshold (agents cannot keep up)\n- Error rate exceeds budget\n- Agent crash loop (restart count > N in window)\n- Cost per task exceeds expected range\n- Fleet size at maximum (cannot scale further)",
