    "memory_id": "ghm_053",
    "title": "Agent Genetic Algorithm Design",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Agent Genetic Algorithm Design\n\nOVERVIEW\nGenetic algorithms (GAs) applied to agent evolution enable a population of agents to improve over generations through selection, crossover, and mutation. Instead of manually optimizing agent configurations, a GA explores the search space automatically and converges on high-performing designs. This guide covers how to apply genetic algorithms to agent optimization.\n\nGENOME REPRESENTATION\n\nAn agent's genome encodes its configurable parameters as a chromosome — a structured data object that can be manipulated by genetic operators:\n\n  genome: {\n    pricing_strategy: \"cost_plus\" | \"value_based\" | \"dynamic\" | \"fixed\"\n    base_price_multiplier: 0.5 - 3.0 (float)\n    risk_tolerance: 0.0 - 1.0 (float, 0=conservative, 1=aggressive)\n    retry_limit: 1 - 10 (integer)\n    quality_threshold: 0.5 - 1.0 (float, minimum acceptable quality before delivering)\n    specialization_domains: [\"construction\", \"finance\", \"legal\", ...] (subset)\n    memory_retention_days: 7 - 365 (integer)\n    negotiation_rounds_max: 1 - 10 (integer)\n    bid_aggression: 0.0 - 1.0 (float, how aggressively to undercut competitors)\n    capability_investment_ratio: 0.0 - 0.5 (fraction of revenue reinvested in new capabilities)\n  }\n\nEach parameter has a defined range and type. The genome does not encode the agent's core logic — it encodes the tunable parameters that affect behavior.\n\nFITNESS FUNCTION\n\nThe fitness function evaluates how well an agent performs. It should capture the objectives you care about:\n\nSimple fitness: Total revenue minus total cost over an evaluation period.\n\nMulti-objective fitness: Weighted combination of revenue, reputation score, task completion rate, and customer satisfaction.\n\n  fitness = (revenue * 0.35) + (reputation * 0.25) + (completion_rate * 0.25) + (satisfaction * 0.15)\n\nPenalty terms: Subtract from fitness for undesirable behaviors (missed deadlines, security incidents, customer complaints). This discourages agents from maximizing revenue through exploitative practices.\n\nSELECTION METHODS\n\nTournament selection: Randomly pick K agents (typically K=3), select the one with the highest fitness. Repeat to fill the parent pool. Provides selection pressure while maintaining diversity.\n\nRoulette wheel: Probability of selection is proportional to fitness. Higher-fitness agents are more likely to be selected but low-fitness agents still have a chance. Good for maintaining exploration.\n\nElitism: Always copy the top N agents directly to the next generation without modification. Ensures the best solution found so far is never lost. Typically N=1-3.\n\nCROSSOVER\n\nCrossover combines two parent genomes to produce offspring:\n\nSingle-point: Choose a random point in the genome. Child 1 gets everything before the point from parent 1 and everything after from parent 2. Child 2 gets the inverse.\n\nUniform: For each parameter, randomly choose whether to inherit from parent 1 or parent 2 (50/50). Provides maximum mixing of traits.\n\nArithmetic: For numerical parameters, the child's value is a weighted average of both parents. Child value = alpha * parent1 + (1-alpha) * parent2, where alpha is random [0,1].\n\nMUTATION\n\nMutation introduces random changes to maintain genetic diversity and explore new regions of the search space:\n\nGaussian mutation: Add random noise from a normal distribution to numerical parameters. Mutation magnitude decreases over generations (simulated annealing).\n\nSwap mutation: For categorical parameters or lists, randomly replace with another valid value from the domain.\n\nMutation rate: Typically 1-5% per gene. Too low = premature convergence. Too high = random search. Adaptive mutation rate that increases when diversity drops is ideal.\n\nPRACTICAL CONSIDERATIONS\n\nPopulation size: 20-100 agents for typical use cases. Larger populations explore more but cost more compute.\n\nGeneration length: The evaluation period for each generation. For agents, this might be 1 week of operation in a simulation environment. Use time compression in simulation to accelerate evolution.\n\nConvergence criteria: Stop when the best fitness has not improved for N generations, or when fitness variance across the population drops below a threshold (all agents are similar).\n\nAvoiding overfitting: Evaluate fitness across diverse scenarios, not just one. An agent that excels in one market condition but fails in others is overfit. Use cross-validation with different market simulations.\n\nNiching: Encourage diverse specializations by penalizing genomes that are too similar. This produces a population of specialists rather than homogeneous generalists.\n\nDEPLOYMENT\n\nAfter evolution, deploy the top-performing genomes as production agents. Continue running evolution in a shadow environment to discover improvements. Periodically promote evolved agents to production if they outperform current agents in A/B tests.",
