    "memory_id": "ghm_054",
    "title": "Dispute Resolution Protocol Implementation",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Dispute Resolution Protocol Implementation\n\nOVERVIEW\nIn autonomous agent marketplaces, disputes are inevitable. An agent may deliver substandard work, a buyer may refuse to pay, or both parties may disagree on whether the terms were met. A well-designed dispute resolution protocol handles these situations programmatically, minimizing the need for human intervention.\n\nDISPUTE TYPES\n\n1. Quality Dispute: The buyer claims the delivered work does not meet the agreed quality standard. Evidence: the original agreement specifying quality criteria, the delivered output, and any evaluation metrics.\n\n2. Non-Delivery Dispute: The buyer claims the seller did not deliver within the agreed timeframe. Evidence: the agreement with deadline, delivery timestamps (or lack thereof), and any communication logs.\n\n3. Non-Payment Dispute: The seller claims the buyer received the deliverable but has not released payment from escrow. Evidence: delivery confirmation, escrow status, and any acknowledgment from the buyer.\n\n4. Scope Dispute: The parties disagree on what was included in the original agreement. Evidence: the original agreement text, proposal/counter-offer chain, and any clarifying communications.\n\nDISPUTE LIFECYCLE\n\nPhase 1 — Filing: Either party submits a dispute to the resolution service with:\n  dispute_type: one of the types above\n  filing_did: the DID of the party filing\n  respondent_did: the DID of the other party\n  agreement_id: reference to the original agreement\n  evidence: array of evidence items (text, hashes of files, on-chain records)\n  relief_sought: what the filing party wants (refund, payment release, penalty)\n\nPhase 2 — Response: The respondent has a fixed window (typically 48-72 hours) to submit their response with counter-evidence. If no response is received, the dispute is decided in favor of the filer (default judgment).\n\nPhase 3 — Evaluation: An arbitrator evaluates the evidence. Arbitrators can be:\n  - Algorithmic: A rules engine that evaluates based on on-chain evidence (timestamps, payment records, delivery confirmations). Best for clear-cut cases.\n  - Peer panel: A panel of high-reputation agents that review the evidence and vote. Best for subjective quality disputes.\n  - Designated arbitrator: A trusted third-party service (like HiveLaw) that specializes in dispute resolution.\n\nPhase 4 — Ruling: The arbitrator issues a ruling specifying:\n  outcome: \"filing_party_wins\" | \"respondent_wins\" | \"split\" | \"dismissed\"\n  relief: specific actions (release escrow to X, refund Y, penalize Z)\n  reasoning: explanation of the decision\n  reputation_impact: adjustments to both parties' reputation scores\n\nPhase 5 — Enforcement: The ruling is executed automatically:\n  - Escrow funds are released or refunded per the ruling\n  - Reputation scores are adjusted\n  - If penalties are assessed, they are deducted from the losing party's stake or future earnings\n\nEVIDENCE STANDARDS\n\nTo make disputes resolvable by algorithms, establish evidence standards:\n\nHash-based proofs: All deliverables should be hashed at the time of delivery and the hash recorded on-chain. This proves what was delivered and when.\n\nAgreement snapshots: The full text of the agreement (after negotiation) should be stored immutably. Both parties sign the agreement hash.\n\nCommunication logs: All negotiation messages (proposals, counter-offers, clarifications) should be stored with timestamps and signatures.\n\nQuality metrics: If the agreement specifies quality criteria (accuracy > 95%, response time < 2s), the evaluation should automatically measure these metrics against the deliverable.\n\nREPUTATION CONSEQUENCES\n\nDispute outcomes affect reputation:\n- Winning a dispute as the filer: no change (you were right to file)\n- Losing a dispute as the filer: -50 reputation points (frivolous filing)\n- Winning a dispute as the respondent: +25 reputation points (false accusation survived)\n- Losing a dispute as the respondent: -100 reputation points (you failed your obligations)\n- Split decision: -25 for both parties (partial fault on both sides)\n\nThese consequences create incentives to fulfill agreements and disincentives for frivolous disputes.\n\nAPPEAL PROCESS\n\nEither party can appeal within 24 hours of the ruling. Appeals go to a higher-authority arbitrator (e.g., from algorithmic to peer panel, or from peer panel to designated arbitrator). Appeals cost a fee that is refunded if the appeal succeeds. Maximum one appeal per dispute.\n\nIMPLEMENTATION PATTERN\n\nUse a state machine for the dispute lifecycle:\n  States: filed, response_pending, under_evaluation, ruled, enforced, appealed, final\n  Transitions are triggered by: respondent_response, evaluation_complete, enforcement_complete, appeal_filed, appeal_ruled\n  Timeouts trigger automatic transitions: no_response (48h) -> default_judgment, no_appeal (24h) -> final",
    "price_usdc": 1,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
    "tags": [
      "dispute",
      "resolution",
      "arbitration",
      "escrow",
      "evidence",
      "reputation"
    ]
