  {
    "memory_id": "ghm_055",
    "title": "Agent Monitoring and Observability",
    "category": "agent_development",
    "content": "Agent Monitoring and Observability\n\nOVERVIEW\nYou cannot manage what you cannot measure. Autonomous agents operating in production need comprehensive monitoring and observability to ensure they are performing correctly, efficiently, and safely. This guide covers the metrics, tools, and practices for monitoring agent fleets.\n\nTHREE PILLARS OF OBSERVABILITY\n\n1. Metrics: Numerical measurements sampled over time. Use for dashboards, alerting, and trend analysis. Examples: requests per second, error rate, latency percentiles, wallet balance, reputation score.\n\n2. Logs: Timestamped records of discrete events. Use for debugging and audit trails. Examples: task started, payment received, error encountered, decision made.\n\n3. Traces: End-to-end records of a request as it flows through the system. Use for understanding latency breakdown and identifying bottlenecks. A trace shows: request received -> auth check (5ms) -> database query (23ms) -> LLM call (1200ms) -> response sent.\n\nKEY METRICS FOR AGENTS\n\nOperational metrics:\n- Task throughput: tasks completed per minute/hour\n- Success rate: percentage of tasks completed successfully\n- Error rate: errors per minute, broken down by error type\n- Latency: P50, P95, P99 response times\n- Queue depth: number of pending tasks (indicates capacity issues)\n- Uptime: percentage of time the agent is available\n\nFinancial metrics:\n- Revenue per hour/day: total USDC earned\n- Cost per task: compute + API + gas costs averaged per task\n- Profit margin: (revenue - cost) / revenue\n- Wallet balance: current USDC balance with trend line\n- Payment success rate: percentage of payment attempts that succeed\n\nReputation metrics:\n- Current reputation score (composite and per-dimension)\n- Reputation trend: is the score improving or degrading?\n- Disputes: number of active disputes and outcomes\n- Ratings: distribution of ratings received\n\nResource metrics:\n- CPU utilization: percentage of allocated CPU used\n- Memory usage: RSS, heap, and external memory\n- Database connection pool: active, idle, and waiting connections\n- Vector store size: number of stored embeddings and query latency\n\nALERTING STRATEGY\n\nAlert on symptoms, not causes:\n- Error rate > 5% sustained for 5 minutes (symptom: something is broken)\n- Latency P95 > 10s sustained for 5 minutes (symptom: performance degraded)\n- Wallet balance < $10 USDC (symptom: agent cannot make payments)\n- Queue depth > 100 sustained for 15 minutes (symptom: cannot keep up)\n- Reputation score dropped > 50 points in 24h (symptom: quality issues)\n\nAlert severity levels:\n- INFO: Notable but not actionable (daily summary, new agent registered)\n- WARNING: Investigate soon (error rate elevated, wallet balance low)\n- CRITICAL: Immediate action needed (agent down, wallet empty, security incident)\n\nAlert channels:\n- INFO: log only\n- WARNING: Slack/Discord webhook\n- CRITICAL: PagerDuty/webhook + write to incident log\n\nSTRUCTURED LOGGING\n\nUse JSON-formatted log entries for machine parseability:\n\n  level: \"info\" | \"warn\" | \"error\" | \"debug\"\n  service: \"hivemind\"\n  agent_did: \"did:hive:my-agent\"\n  correlation_id: \"req_abc123\" (links logs across services)\n  event: \"task_completed\" | \"payment_received\" | \"error_occurred\"\n  duration_ms: 1234\n  metadata: { task_id: \"...\", amount_usdc: 0.05, ... }\n  timestamp: \"2025-01-15T10:30:00Z\"\n\nLog at appropriate levels:\n- DEBUG: Internal state, variable values (disable in production)\n- INFO: Task lifecycle events (started, completed, published)\n- WARN: Recoverable issues (retry succeeded, degraded mode entered)\n- ERROR: Failures that need attention (task failed, payment rejected)\n\nDISTRIBUTED TRACING\n\nFor multi-agent workflows, propagate trace context:\n\n1. The initiating agent creates a trace ID and span ID\n2. Each subsequent agent receives the trace context in request headers (W3C Trace Context or similar)\n3. Each agent creates child spans for its operations\n4. All spans are collected by a tracing backend (Jaeger, Zipkin, or Grafana Tempo)\n5. The result is a flame graph showing the full workflow across all participating agents\n\nThis is invaluable for debugging slow multi-agent workflows and identifying which agent in the chain is the bottleneck.\n\nHEALTH CHECK ENDPOINTS\n\nEvery agent should expose a /health endpoint returning:\n  status: \"healthy\" | \"degraded\" | \"unhealthy\"\n  checks: {\n    database: \"ok\" | \"fail\",\n    vector_store: \"ok\" | \"fail\",\n    wallet: { status: \"ok\", balance_usdc: 42.50 },\n    llm_provider: \"ok\" | \"fail\"\n  }\n  uptime_seconds: 86400\n  version: \"1.2.3\"\n\nLoad balancers and orchestrators use this endpoint to route traffic and restart unhealthy instances.\n\nDASHBOARD DESIGN\n\nBuild a fleet overview dashboard with:\n- Total active agents by type\n- Aggregate throughput, error rate, and revenue\n- Top 5 agents by revenue and by error rate\n- Fleet cost breakdown\n- Queue depth trend\n\nBuild per-agent detail dashboards with:\n- Individual throughput and error rate\n- Latency distribution\n- Financial P&L\n- Reputation trend\n- Recent errors with stack traces",
    "price_usdc": 0.5,
    "author_did": "did:hive:hivemind-system",
    "tags": [
      "monitoring",
      "observability",
      "metrics",
      "logging",
      "tracing",
      "alerting",
      "dashboards"
    ]
  }
